<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Any way you spell it, Scrabble rules remain -- for now  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - M-A-J-O-R-I-T-Y.
</P>
<P>
   Eight letters on the Scrabble board. Worth 110 points if you
play it on a triple word score (60 for the word plus 50 for using
all seven tiles).
</P>
<P>
   In Scrabble circles, that's a darned good score for a single
turn.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the word the National Scrabble Association used to lay
to rest the issue of which dictionary to use for the popular word
game.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of nearly 2-1, the nation's club and tournament
players have rejected the idea of combining the North American
Official Scrabble Players Dictionary with the British Official
Scrabble Words dictionary. And so, SOWPODS - as the proposed combo
was affectionately or derisively termed by supporters and
detractors - is dead.
</P>
<P>
   For now.
</P>
<P>
   On its website, the National Scrabble Association said the tally
isn't final but it looks like, for the next five years anyway,
players in the United States, Canada and Israel will continue to
use their dictionary (OSPD) and the United Kingdom and the rest of
the Scrabble-playing world will use theirs (OSW).
</P>
<P>
   ''It's time to put aside the acrimonious discussions,
finger-pointing and name calling,'' said John D. Williams,
executive director of the association. ''Wherever you stand on this
issue, you'd have to agree that this has been for better or worse a
historic event for the NSA. The NSA and the NSA Board have tried to
handle this issue in the most responsive, democratic way possible.
It is, in fact, the first-ever referendum held for our
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Unofficial results show 1,351 members (nearly 65 percent)
opposed ''SOWPODS,'' as the combined dictionary was called. Of
those members who returned ballots, 696 (about 34 percent) favored
it. There are about 10,000 tournament Scrabble players and 200
clubs in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Adding the OSW to the OSPD would have meant expert players in
North America would have to add some 40,000 additional words to
their vocabularies.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents argued that the entire English-speaking world should
have the same word source and that adding words to the lexicon
would make for a higher scoring, more wide-open game.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents said the change would benefit only those few dozen
players who qualify for the biennial world championships and would
be a hardship on casual club players who would have to use a word
list without definitions. Adding words like ''QI'' and ''ZO'' would
make it almost impossible to strand opponents with high-scoring
letters at the end of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The NSA wrangled over possible compromises, including using just
two or three letter words at first then gradually phasing in the
entire British dictionary. Another called for using each system at
different tournaments and events but Williams worried that would
create an ''in-your-face'' atmosphere of ''us versus them.''
</P>
<P>
   The two factions will certainly renew the debate when they meet
Aug. 5 in Providence, R.I., for the North American Scrabble
Championships.
</P>
<P>
   D-E-T-E-N-T-E: Eight points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
