<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, July 22, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cheney Said To Be Bush's Top VP Pick
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two highly placed GOP officials said Texas Gov. George W.
Bush is seriously considering former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney as his
Republican running mate, turning to a respected Washington insider in the final
days of his search for a vice presidential candidate. The former lawmaker, White
House chief of staff and Defense Secretary -- the man heading up Bush's search
team -- thrust himself into the process by changing his voter registration
Friday from Texas to Wyoming. Cheney, who is considered the leading candidate,
made the move to ensure he is eligible for the job if the governor decides to
offer it, said the officials who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israel Makes Jerusalem Concession
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- The United States is promoting an Israeli-initiated
proposal to recognize Palestinian administrative control over Arab neighborhoods
of Jerusalem, in a bid to clear the most stubborn obstacle to a Camp David peace
agreement. The proposal conveyed the ''characteristic'' of Palestinian
sovereignty in the eastern area of the contested city -- a long-cherished
Palestinian goal, an Israeli Cabinet officer said in Jerusalem. Reacting coolly
to the ideas, Hassan Abdel Rahman, Washington representative of the Palestine
Liberation Organization, said Friday: ''Short of total Palestinian sovereignty
over East Jerusalem, there is not a ground for an agreement.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Colorado Fire Doubles in Size
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MESA VERDE NATIONAL PARK, Colo. (AP) -- Fire crews called in reinforcements
to battle a 3,500-acre wildfire that doubled in size Friday, spreading quickly
across tinder-dry mesas and canyons and forcing the evacuation of 1,000 tourists
from Mesa Verde National Park. About 350 firefighters, aided by slurry bombers,
were fighting flames in rugged, steep terrain on the eastern boundary of the
park, about 260 miles southwest of Denver.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Hawaii Tour Copter Crashes, 7 Die
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WAILUKU, Hawaii (AP) -- A tour helicopter on a sightseeing flight crashed
Friday on the island of Maui, killing all seven people aboard, the company's
owner said. The Blue Hawaiian Helicopters AS355 twin-engine aircraft was
reported missing after it failed to return from a 35-minute tour of the rugged
west Maui mountains. The wreckage was found in a valley near the chopper's last
known radar fix, said Wil Absher of the Coast Guard's Joint Coordination Rescue
Center in Honolulu.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton, Putin Discuss Military
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NAGO, Okinawa (AP) -- Facing a pivotal decision about building a U.S. missile
defense shield, President Clinton expressed doubts Saturday about North Korea's
offer to abandon its missile program in exchange for Western help in launching
space satellites. Clinton said North Korea's proposal needs to be explored but
added, ''It's not clear to me exactly what the offer is and what is being
requested and the time for it. North Korea's suspected missile ambitions are a
key factor in the U.S. drive to develop a missile shield to protect all 50
states from nuclear attack. Clinton is to decide in the next few months whether
to move ahead with the controversial program, heatedly opposed by Russia.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
USDA To Stop Stamping Imported Meat
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Meat imported from other countries and inspected in the
United States soon will no longer carry USDA grade stamps, the Agriculture
Department announced Friday. Currently, all meat inspected in the United States,
regardless of where it is produced, gets a USDA stamp such as ''prime,''
''choice'' or ''select. The USDA said it was changing the practice because of
consumer confusion over origin of meat products. U.S. ranchers had sought the
change, saying the USDA stamp serves as a form of advertising not meant for
foreign meats.
</P>
