<HEADLINE> Israel Newspaper Plans Web Radio  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Jerusalem Post reporters are supposed to carry
tape recorders and microphones these days to gather sound for the
newspaper's new Internet radio station.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion to online radio hasn't pleased everyone. Some
veteran notebook-and-pencil reporters refused to tote the
equipment, said David Zev Harris, the station's news director.
</P>
<P>
   ''But the younger ones are keen. They find radio sexy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The paper's Internet radio service went online May 31. Six radio
staffers provide news updates, reports and features about Israel
and the Jewish world, using material they gather and the resources
of the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said the new station reflects the paper's policy to be a
news provider, rather than just a print outlet. The Internet Web
site recorded 4.8 million hits in May, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters noted that the newspaper, owned by the Canadian
Hollinger Group Ltd., is up for sale, and the radio channel could
add value to the property.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, 34, worked for the BBC in London before moving here in
1996. Station manager Michal Cohen and presenter Teisha Bader came
over from Radio West, a popular English-language pirate station
shut down last year by Israeli authorities.
</P>
<P>
   In the radio's three-room offices in the Jerusalem Post
building, production manager David Starck, who moved here from
Chicago in 1996, was updating the station's program, inserting the
latest sports report.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a microphone, he used a desktop computer to feed the
digitalized sports report through Everstream, a Cleveland-based
company that serves about 150 newspaper audio Web sites in the
United States, providing mostly music programming. The Jerusalem
Post is Everstream's first foreign client.
</P>
<P>
   Instantly, the new sports report appeared on the station's
Internet menu. Harris said this underlines the advantage of the
station over on-the-air broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   If a listener tunes in to a radio newscast a minute late, he
misses the top story, Harris said. The newspaper radio service
allows a listener to start a newscast whenever he wants. Also, he
or she can pick a specific story or feature, instead of listening
to an entire program.
</P>
<P>
   The technology allows the radio sound to play while the listener
uses the same computer for other purposes. ''It's just like having
a radio playing in the background,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://jpostradio.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
