<HEADLINE> Labor To Fete GOP Lawmakers  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Three Republican congressmen will be feted at
the GOP convention next month by an unlikely source -- 16 labor
unions.
</P>
<P>
   Ranging from the Air Line Pilots Association to the United
Brotherhood of Carpenters and Joiners, the unions, joined by the
AFL-CIO's Building and Construction Trades Department, are honoring
Reps. Jack Quinn of New York, Frank LoBiondo of New Jersey and Ray
LaHood of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the AFL-CIO has begun its election-year TV
campaign with ads in five key districts held by congressional
Republicans facing tight races. The AFL-CIO is targeting them for
failing to support a Medicare prescription drug plan backed by the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   All three GOP lawmakers to be honored Aug. 2 sit on the House
Transportation and Infrastructure Committee. Half of the unions
sponsoring the reception represent transportation industry workers.
</P>
<P>
   The three congressmen ''have been very good on labor
transportation issues,'' said Jeff Zack, a spokesman for the
Association of Flight Attendants, one of the unions sponsoring the
reception. ''We support politicians who support issues important to
flight attendants.''
</P>
<P>
   Zack said the lawmakers helped push through provisions that gave
increased protection for flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Bucking Republican leaders, Quinn played a key role in 1996 in
the successful effort to raise the minimum wage. The AFL-CIO has
given him a lifetime pro-labor voting record of 55 percent.
LoBiondo's lifetime record is 46 percent. LaHood has a much lower
rating, 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''If labor unions want to get together in support of
Republicans, we're all for it,'' said National Republican
Congressional Committee spokeswoman Marit Babin.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this show of support for some GOP lawmakers, organized
labor is still firmly planted on the Democratic side. Since Jan. 1,
1999, unions and their members have given $40.2 million to
Democratic candidates and party committees, compared with $3.1
million given to Republicans, according to the Campaign Study
Group, a nonpartisan consulting firm that analyzes campaign finance
data.
</P>
<P>
   And when the AFL-CIO's 30 transportation unions met on Thursday
and Friday, they heard from Vice President Al Gore, Senate
Democratic leader Tom Daschle and House Democratic leader Dick
Gephardt. Their Republican counterparts were not invited.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the AFL-CIO is spending ''a couple hundred thousand
dollars'' for ads in the five congressional districts, spokeswoman
Denise Mitchell said. The commercials began airing this week in the
districts of Republican Reps. Charles Bass of New Hampshire, Ernie
Fletcher of Kentucky, Don Sherwood of Pennsylvania, and Jim Rogan
and Steve Kuykendall of California.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very focused on trying to be sure working family issues
get elevated in the debate,'' Mitchell said. ''Obviously members
(of Congress) who are more sensitive are people who are in marginal
races.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
