<HEADLINE> Bizarre Roll Call For Thai Election  </HEADLINE>
By MATTHEW PENNINGTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- A former manager of the national soccer
team, a flight attendant known for shadowing the prime minister and
a political veteran who has capitalized on surviving a bomb attack.
</P>
<P>
   Not characters in a spy movie, but some of the candidates in
Sunday's election to decide who runs Thailand's urban nightmare --
Bangkok, a metropolis of 10 million people cursed by traffic jams,
floods and chronic pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-three candidates, most doomed to be distant also-rans,
are running for the city governorship. It carries a monthly salary
of only $2,500, and the winner will take flak for everything from
the state of the sidewalks to the begging elephants and their
handlers cluttering the streets.
</P>
<P>
   But even national political heavyweights are challenging for the
job, which oversees a $600 million annual budget. The result of the
election could affect which party grabs parliamentary seats in
Bangkok in general elections this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a 24-hour-a-day job,'' says outgoing governor Bhichit
Rattakul, credited with making Bangkok a slightly greener place
during his four-year tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ''My advice for my successor is to stay out of politics, and
save the time for smoothing out the traffic and planting trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Three decades of rapacious development, slowed only by the Asian
economic crisis that struck in 1997, have left the city with
brackish waterways, just a handful of public parks and inadequate
roads that lead to almost constant gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates with little hope of winning more than a bit of
publicity have been promoting unlikely cures for Bangkok's ills.
</P>
<P>
   An ex-infantry commander who campaigns in camouflage fatigues
wants to employ 50,000 security guards to fight drugs and crime.
</P>
<P>
   A former flight attendant -- who made her name by sticking to
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai like a starstruck teen-ager -- proposes
that Bangkok children study at home via television so they don't
cause traffic jams by traveling to school.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are always opportunists who will present themselves to
the Bangkok electorate and expect to create a new fad and hope
they'll get elected,'' said Pasuk Phongpaichit, lecturer at the
city's Chulalongkorn University.
</P>
<P>
   The man favored to win is sharp-tongued political veteran Samak
Sundaravej, who has been a national lawmaker 10 times and deputy
premier three times. The 65-year-old says if he loses this election
he will become a talk show host.
</P>
<P>
   His main rival is Sudarat Keyuraphan, 39, from the new Thai Rak
Thai party, which could form the next national government --
especially if it proves popular in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
   Former Thailand soccer manager Thawatchai Sajakul, 57, is the
ruling national Democrat Party's candidate. Because he is unlikely
to win, the government is hoping Samak does in order to shut Thai
Rak Thai out.
</P>
<P>
   Samak, a conservative who made his mark in the 1970s before
democracy got a proper foothold, fiercely opposes political reforms
Thailand adopted after the economic crisis to fight graft and make
government more transparent.
</P>
<P>
   He says critics who accuse him of supporting a military massacre
of protesting students in 1976 were responsible for a bomb blast at
one of his rallies on July 13, which injured eight people.
</P>
<P>
   Playing on public sympathy after the bombing, Samak has surged
ahead in opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's 100,000 votes gone just like that,'' Sudarat was quoted
as saying in the Bangkok Post newspaper the day after the blast.
</P>
<P>
   Residents just hope to see some of the city's problems solved.
</P>
<P>
   Pornchai Sae Jiew, 43, a drinks vendor, wants the governor to
make good on something every candidate has promised -- dealing with
traffic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Thawat Phooyaem, 55, a blind lottery ticket seller, wants better
access in the city for the disabled, but has no faith in Thai
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ''They come to meet us at the handicapped club and promise
everything we ask for. But when they win, they forget all their
promises,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-22-00 0113 </TRAILER>
