<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Monks Nix Changes  </HEADLINE>
By DILSHIKA JAYAMAHA
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- President Chandrika Kumaratunga's hope
to end the war with Tamil Tiger rebels has hit a new snag, with Sri
Lanka's powerful Buddhist monks opposing the government's proposed
constitutional changes to allow Tamils more autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sri Lanka's Buddhist clergy generally preach
nonviolence, they have urged the government to carry on its war
against Tamil militants. They say the country's minority Tamils,
who are mostly Hindus, should not be given any special privileges.
</P>
<P>
   The monks said Friday they would oppose the government's
proposed draft constitution, to be presented to Parliament before
Aug. 24, because it makes too many concessions to the Tamils.
</P>
<P>
   ''This plan is unacceptable to us and we reject it,'' Maduluwawe
Sobitha, president of the National Council of the Buddhist Clergy,
told The Associated Press on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This plan betrays Buddhism,'' Sobitha said, expressing fear
that under the proposed constitution Buddhism would lose its status
as the dominant religion in Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
   Monks in Sri Lanka -- where 76 percent of the people follow the
teachings of Buddha -- wield immense influence.
</P>
<P>
   Tamils make up 3.2 million of the country's 18.6 million people,
and Tamil rebels have been fighting for 17 years for an independent
homeland in the north and east. The war has claimed 62,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the new constitution have not been made public, but
general outlines have been discussed. The government and the main
opposition United National Party have agreed on the constitutional
changes and they have enough votes to pass it in Parliament before
the session ends and elections are called.
</P>
<P>
   But the government needs broad support to make the plan work.
</P>
<P>
   It already has been rejected by Tamil political parties and the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam rebels. The parties say the draft
constitution does not give regions enough autonomy. The rebels say
they will settle for nothing less than a homeland.
</P>
<P>
   The Buddhist monks have told Kumaratunga, who wants to end the
war, to finish the rebels off militarily.
</P>
<P>
   ''We now advise you to act as a patriotic head of state by
ceasing all negotiations immediately, crushing this cruel terrorism
without delay by the use of state power. Toward this end you will
get our blessings,'' the country's top four monks said in a March
letter to Kumaratunga, who is a Buddhist.
</P>
<P>
   The letter came a month after the government announced its plan
to discuss constitutional changes.
</P>
<P>
   The government is also bound by the constitution, which says it
is the duty of the state to protect and foster Buddhism. The
country's 30,000 monks have influenced political decisions in the
past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-22-00 0156 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000722.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Plans More Force in Lebanon  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Secretary-General Kofi Annan has proposed
that the U.N. force remain in Lebanon for another six months,
provided Lebanon allows peacekeepers to deploy toward the Israeli
border and Lebanese forces strengthen their presence there.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon has said it would consent to U.N. deployment to border
areas only after Israeli violations of the U.N.-designated line of
withdrawal have been corrected. On Friday, U.N. spokesman Fred
Eckhard said Israel had fixed all but two of those violations.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon also has said that it would deploy additional troops and
internal security forces to the south after Israel's violations of
the line are corrected.
</P>
<P>
   Annan issued his report on the status of the U.N. mission as
U.N. and Lebanese officers wrapped up weeks of border inspections
to check the violations and just before U.N. envoy Terje
Roed-Larsen returns to Beirut to discuss further deployment of
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Israel invaded Lebanon in 1978 and occupied part of southern
Lebanon as a buffer against guerrilla attacks on its northern
communities from 1985 until its withdrawal on May 24.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. cartographers last month drew the line between Lebanon and
Israel to confirm Israel's withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   In his report, Annan said it was fortunate that large-scale
violence didn't break out after the unilateral withdrawal and when
Hezbollah guerrillas moved into areas formerly under control of
Israel and its allied militias.
</P>
<P>
   ''I note, in particular, that the fighters of the Lebanese
resistance conducted themselves in a controlled manner that
deserves to be acknowledged; there were no acts of vengeance as
they reclaimed the area vacated by the Israeli forces,'' Annan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has complained about border violations by Lebanon. It
said Thursday it has notified the United Nations of 172 violations.
The Israeli army said it had filed 49 complaints this week alone
for violations including stones and metal objects thrown at
soldiers guarding the border and at farm workers in fields nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Israel also has called for the United Nations to fully deploy to
the border areas in line with 1978 resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   In his report, Annan said he would recommend the Security
Council keep the mission in Lebanon for another six months ''on the
understanding that the force will be enabled to deploy and function
fully throughout its area of operation, and that the Lebanese
authorities will strengthen their own presence in the area.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan also called for countries to contribute troops to the
current 5,075-member force. And he appealed for international
assistance to help southern Lebanon recover from the Israeli
occupation, including removing land mines and starting development
projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
