<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 02:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-8 leaders Focus On Third World  </HEADLINE>
By THOMAS WAGNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAGO, Okinawa (AP) -- The Group of Eight industrial powers
pledged Saturday to help poor nations join the information
technology revolution so they can one day leave the Third World
behind.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the last G-8 summit President Clinton will attend
with the leaders of Japan, Italy, Britain, Germany, France, Canada
and Russia, the leaders agreed to pool efforts to expand Internet
access and make it more affordable in developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone should be able to enjoy access to information and
communications networks,'' a charter signed by the members said.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders also said governments should avoid regulating
information technology too tightly, and they pledged protections
for intellectual property rights in cyberspace. A task force will
report on the success of its efforts at next year's G-8 summit in
Genoa, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments:
</P>
<P>
   --Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori and Clinton agreed to
extend for a fourth year trade talks on a broad range of business
sectors, from telecommunications to financial services and
pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   --Clinton said he would leave Okinawa a few hours early on Sunday
to return to the Mideast peace talks being held at Camp David in
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   --Clinton questioned North Korea's reported offer during its
summit this week with Russia to abandon its missile program in
exchange for help in launching space satellites. ''It is not clear
to me what the offer is...what is being requested in return,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   --Japanese officials said Clinton expressed regret over a recent
attack by a drunken U.S. Marine on an Okinawan girl that rekindled
opposition to the many American military bases on the island.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the G-8 leaders congratulated themselves for the
robust global economy and marveled at the distance traveled since
the Asian financial crisis of three years ago. With the notable
exception of Japan, many of the hardest-hit crisis countries are
staging strong recoveries.
</P>
<P>
   The G-8 leaders said while prospects for world economic growth
have improved, there are worries that a huge run-up in oil prices
could spoil the good times.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders also promised to share global prosperity with poor
countries, speeding up the process of forgiving their heavy burden
of debt or at least rescheduling payments under more favorable
terms.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting on the Okinawa island of semitropical beaches and coral
reefs, the leaders began the day Saturday by planting a new, local
pine tree in front of the summit venue, the seaside Bankoku Shinryo
conference hall. It was built for the summit and named after the
inscription on a 15th century bell, which in Japanese means ''a
bridge between nations.''
</P>
<P>
   During a private meting with the Japanese prime minister,
Clinton said he regrets such incidents as the recent alleged attack
on a teen-age Okinawan girl by a drunken 19-year-old Marine. The
man allegedly broke into the girl's home on July 3, crawled into
her bed and fondled her.
</P>
<P>
   The girl's mother removed her screaming daughter from the bed,
and the unidentified serviceman was later arrested as he slept
there.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, one day before Clinton arrived in Okinawa for the
G-8 summit, tens of thousands of Japanese held hands around the
Kadena U.S. military base to demand the reduction of bases and U.S.
servicemen.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The official G-8 summit site: http://www.g8kyushu-okinawa.go.jp
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-22-00 0253 </TRAILER>
