<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 08:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Korea Decries Anti-Missile System  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- North Korea lashed out at Japan on
Saturday for backing Washington's proposed anti-missile defense
system, calling its island neighbor ''cancer in the international
community.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Today the biggest destabilizing military factor in East Asia
is the development of the 'Theater Missile Defense' system jointly
stepped up by the United States and Japan,'' the North's official
foreign news outlet, KCNA, said in a commentary.
</P>
<P>
   It accused Japan of trying to gain military supremacy in East
Asia through the missile defense program.
</P>
<P>
   ''This proves that Japan is the most unstable state in the world
that sparks a new arms race,'' said the commentary, monitored in
Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two years ago, the communist North shocked East Asia by
test-firing a long-range missile that flew over Japan and landed in
the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Vladimir Putin, who met North Korean leader
Kim Jong Il this week in Pyongyang, later indicated that North
Korea may abandon its missile program in exchange for help in
putting peaceful satellites into orbit.
</P>
<P>
   The North's missile program is one of the reasons the United
States wants to build its missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   KCNA accused the United States and Japan of fabricating missile
threats from the North to justify their missile defense program.
North Korea says its rocket programs were meant for peaceful
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Other nations, including Russia, China, France and Germany, have
criticized the proposed defense system as a potential threat to the
goal of global disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. missile defense would require an amendment to the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty, which bans national missile
defenses. Russia already has refused to approve such a change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-22-00 0823 </TRAILER>
