<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 09:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China TV Program Gets Taiwanese Host  </HEADLINE>
By ANNIE HUANG
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Prominent Taiwanese political commentator
Li Ao is the host of a new show on China's state-run television,
and he says this is a sign Chinese leaders are becoming more
tolerant of dissent.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-minute program, which aired Friday on Central Television,
was the first time a Taiwanese was the host of a Chinese public
affairs program.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese station picked Li to be the host of the program
because it believed he would ''speak the truth and harbor no
malice,'' said the writer and historian, who ran for president last
March for the small pro-China New Party. Li won about 1 percent of
the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Li said he hoped the weekly program can help resolve the
deep-rooted misunderstandings between Taiwanese and Chinese
resulting from five decades of separation. The two sides split amid
civil war in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unless they are crazy, no rulers would like to aim their
machine guns at people or forbid them to speak out,'' Li told The
Associated Press. ''They did so only when they feel insecure and
fear unrest.''
</P>
<P>
   Li was born in China and fled to Taiwan with Gen. Chiang
Kai-shek's Nationalists after the communists took over the
mainland. He was jailed for years for criticizing Chiang's
authoritarian government.
</P>
<P>
   The writer, who favors eventual reunification with China, has a
talk show on Taiwanese cable television. Although many Taiwanese
don't share his views, they watch his program for his sharp, witty
comments about Taiwanese politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ''The communists have been reasonable and patient about
Taiwan,'' Li told the AP. ''They are reluctant to use force, and
all they want is Taiwan's verbal commitment to be a part of
China.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparing the rival governments to an estranged couple, Li said
China would allow Taiwan to have extramarital affairs but would
never approve a formal divorce.
</P>
<P>
   In the Friday program, Li said he supported the formula of ''one
China, two systems'' proposed by China as a model for
reunification.
</P>
<P>
   Under the system -- used for the former British colony of Hong
Kong after its handover to China in 1997 -- Taiwan would be given
autonomy for 50 years. But most polls say Taiwanese oppose it
because they fear they would lose their political freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ''The two sides can compete under the formula to see which does
better,'' Li said. ''It would allow us to stall on the issue.
Things change so fast and who knows what will happen 50 years
later?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Li said he also told the Chinese audience not to feel hurt by
the snobbish Taiwanese who like to show off their wealth when
visiting the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   The Taiwanese are to be blamed for the poverty of their Chinese
compatriots, which was partly caused by Chiang's shipment of
920,000 ounces of gold from the China to Taiwan when he fled to the
mainland, Li said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are many understandings resulting from political
biases,'' Li said. ''I am the first one to speak the truth across
the Strait.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-22-00 0916 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000722.0036 </DOCNO>
