<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Owner wants to put fire-breathing dragon atop pizza parlor  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NAPLES, N.Y. (AP) - A businessman trying to win permission to
place a remote-control, fire-breathing dragon atop his pizza parlor
wants the village to reimburse him almost $2,600 in expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Dominick Gallo drew 200 people to a public hearing before the
village planning board in mid-July by handing out 100 free ''Fire
Up the Dragon'' T-shirts, sending a giant dragon puppet cruising
the streets and hiring musicians to play ''Puff the Magic Dragon.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallo, who owns Luigi's on Main Street, now thinks the village
board steered him down a fruitless path. He wants to be reimbursed
$2,596.69.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo claims the planning board is asking for too much
information and putting off making a decision. ''I believe now I'm
being played,'' he said in Friday's Daily Messenger of Canandaigua.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo first presented his idea over a year ago to house a dragon
atop Luigi's. The steel likeness would live in a den on the roof
but move to the front of the building every 30 minutes each
evening, when it would roar and spew forth a 10-foot flame.
</P>
<P>
   His application before the village planning board in April led
to a review by a county planning board. The county denied his
request, saying the dragon would distract drivers, and recommended
that the village's Zoning Board of Appeals decide if the dragon is
a sign.
</P>
<P>
   According to village zoning law, signs are not allowed atop
buildings. Because Gallo refuses to treat the dragon as a sign, the
village believed he had to be referred to its planning board. But
Gallo thinks that was a redundant step that wasted his money.
</P>
<P>
   He believes he should have been sent directly to the village's
Zoning Board of Appeals, which is responsible for interpreting his
creation and deciding whether he should be given a variance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
