<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Church Seeks Cease-fire  </HEADLINE>
By CASIMIRIO SIONA
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUANDA, Angola (AP) -- Wrapping up a four-day peace conference,
Angola's religious leaders urged the government and UNITA rebels to
declare a cease-fire as a first step toward ending their protracted
civil war.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released late Friday, the church also asked the
longtime foes to promote a broad dialogue in which civil society
may play a role.
</P>
<P>
   ''This endless war continues to destroy the country, to decimate
its people and to widen the gulf of hatred between Angolans, making
reconciliation ever harder,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Angola's civil war began when Portugal granted the Southwest
African country independence in 1975. Three peace deals have since
failed.
</P>
<P>
   The latest round of fighting was ignited in December 1998 as a
U.N.-brokered pact unraveled amid lingering hostilities and
breaches of the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress for Peace marked the climax of an intensive
campaign, led by the church, for both sides to resume negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   International observers and senior politicians joined the
initiative, as well as grass-roots movements -- a sign that Angola's
civil society is growing bolder and its voice louder.
</P>
<P>
   Public dissent has mostly been stifled as President Jose Eduardo
dos Santos' party, the MPLA, has ruled the country with an iron
fist since independence.
</P>
<P>
   News editors also have been led to self-censorship at times
because dozens of journalists were harassed and jailed since the
government imposed a blackout on war reporting after the resumption
of fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Press freedom also was discussed at the peace congress and news
organizations were urged to contribute to the search for peace by
''transmitting the spirit of forgiveness, tolerance, fraternity,
peace and moral principles.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference opened with a message from Pope John Paul II, who
urged the government and UNITA to negotiate in a bold and
courageous way, so Angolans may finally know peace.
</P>
<P>
   The war has killed, maimed and uprooted millions of people.
Currently, an estimated 1 million people -- nearly a tenth of the
population -- rely on international aid, which has become less
abundant because donor countries are weary of funding relief
programs in a country with a 25-year-old civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Food deliveries have also been hampered by fighting, road
ambushes and land mines which were laid anew by both the government
and UNITA, a Portuguese-language acronym for the National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola.
</P>
<P>
   Angola signed the Mine Ban treaty in 1997. Members of the peace
congress also urged both sides to respect that commitment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
