<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADA 10 years old  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Ten years ago Wednesday, then-President
George Bush signed the Americans with Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   Javier Robles, at the time a student at Rutgers University, knew
just what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ''We went out for a few drinks. That's the way we celebrated in
college,'' said Robles, who suffered a severe spinal cord injury in
his teens when he fell out of a tree.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were ecstatic,'' he said of the ADA, turning serious.
''People with disabilities finally had something to hang their hat
on.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, Robles, now 33, is deputy executive director of
the state Office on Disability Services.
</P>
<P>
   If he needs to, he can take a handicapped accessible NJ Transit
train and bus to his Trenton office from his Edison home.
</P>
<P>
   Before the ADA's enactment, Robles remembers having to book far
in advance for one of NJ Transit's rare accessible buses, if one
was available at all.
</P>
<P>
   It was relatively easy for a wheelchair-bound student to
maneuver at Elizabeth High School, where he attended, but ''the
city itself needed a lot of work,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Later at Rutgers, Robles and fellow disabled students fought for
things that now seem simple - ramps and an electronic door at the
student center.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today, thank goodness, when I go on a date with my wife or
take my daughter to Chuck E. Cheese, I feel more comfortable
leaving my house than I did 10 years ago,'' Robles said.
</P>
<P>
   But even Robles recognizes that the disabled still face
barriers.
</P>
<P>
   The ADA is a civil rights law that guarantees disabled people
equal opportunity in employment, public accommodations,
transportation, state and local government and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Even through the ADA has been on the books for 10 years, Clara
R. Smit, an East Brunswick attorney who specializes in representing
deaf clients, remains busy fighting to make sure the law is
enforced.
</P>
<P>
   Her cases have included an engaged couple who demanded an
interpreter at their Newark City Hall wedding and hospital patients
who insisted on an interpreter when hospital staff offered only to
write instructions.
</P>
<P>
   There are still employers, restaurant owners, public officials
and others who resist full compliance with the law, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the ADA has been very successful in opening up doors.
However, we have a long way to go,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Soden, 39, of Long Branch, is a service coordinator for
an independent living center.
</P>
<P>
   He can relate to his disabled clients, for he has cerebral
palsy.
</P>
<P>
   Soden agreed with Smit that some nondisabled people just don't
understand. For instance, a few years ago, Soden called for a taxi
to take him to work on a rainy day. He explained to the dispatcher
that he was not a ''patient,'' but a commuter with extra baggage, a
roughly 20-pound foldable wheelchair. The taxi company still
refused to pick him up.
</P>
<P>
   ''I got so mad I called the Department of Justice,'' he said.
''But all I wanted was for the owner to apologize.
</P>
<P>
   ''I eventually got what I was looking for,'' Soden said. ''An
apology and an acknowledgment that I was just an individual looking
for a ride to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Housing is also difficult for disabled residents to find, Soden
said. There is a one- to five-year waiting list for accessible
housing that is affordable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm one of the very fortunate ones,'' he said of his secure
job and nearby housing.
</P>
<P>
   Ethan Ellis, executive director of the New Jersey Developmental
Disabilities Council, also has cerebral palsy.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, whose agency is a watchdog over state social services
program, said New Jersey state government is one of the worst
violators of the ADA.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Department of Community Affairs has a handicapped parking
spot in front of their building, but it's a 15-minute drop off. Did
you ever hear of a 15-minute meeting in state government?'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, ''In the private sector, it's done wonders,'' he
said of the law.
</P>
<P>
   More young disabled people are employed, more shopping malls and
theaters are accessible, and more car rentals offer vehicles with
hand controls, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
