<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 12:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> In Wildwood, $70 million arena rising up from beach  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILDWOOD, N.J. (AP) - To barefoot bathers, it is the Sahara by
the sea: an expanse of sand separating the ocean from the
Boardwalk.
</P>
<P>
   One-third of a mile wide in some places, the beaches here are
the envy of sand-starved shore towns up and down the New Jersey
coast. Shrinking space for your beach towel isn't the problem.
Getting your 2-year-old to walk all the way to the water is.
</P>
<P>
   It's so big, it has played host to beach events unthinkable
elsewhere in New Jersey. There have been rodeos, golf tournaments
and Boy Scout jamborees, not to mention permanent fixtures like
monster truck rides, amusement piers and water parks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the state is building a $70 million convention center on
the beach. Not overlooking the beach. On it.
</P>
<P>
   Many locals see the 72,000-square-foot exhibition hall, now
being built by the New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority, as a
kind of economic savior.
</P>
<P>
   With ballrooms, meeting areas and retail outlets, it will play
host to trade shows, civic events, concerts and sports when it
opens in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Sports Authority officials and civic leaders say its location
will be the biggest selling point to conventioneers and meeting
planners.
</P>
<P>
   They, and project architects, say the building will be able to
withstand whatever Mother Nature throws at it.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone thinks it's such a great idea.
</P>
<P>
   ''With what we know today about beaches and their mobility, to
willingly go out and build more things on the beach is not the
brightest move,'' said Stewart Farrell, a beach erosion expert at
the Richard Stockton College of New Jersey. ''They're rolling the
dice with public money.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds D.W. Bennett, executive director of the American Littoral
Society: ''I wouldn't predict a long life for this structure. It's
in harm's way - period.''
</P>
<P>
   The plans, which have been approved by the state Department of
Environmental Protection, call for the structure to be built on the
architectural equivalent of stilts.
</P>
<P>
   Construction began last October.
</P>
<P>
   Already, more than 2,900 chemically-fortified wood pilings have
been driven 35 feet deep into the beach. Capped with concrete, the
pilings were then topped with 10-foot tall concrete columns. The
columns, which are each 2 feet square, will support the floor of
the structure.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Sykes of Atlantic City, who was hired as the local
architect by Seattle designers LMN Architects, said the convention
center's design will allow it to withstand wind, waves and whatever
else comes its way.
</P>
<P>
   The Boardwalk entrance to the building - and the floor of the
hall itself - will be flush with the Boardwalk, about 16 feet above
the beach, Sykes said.
</P>
<P>
   That way, even in a hurricane or Nor'easter, ocean water that
reaches the building will flow underneath, hitting only the
concrete columns, Sykes said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, dunes and snow fences have been erected on three of
the site's four sides. The dunes, reinforced with dune grass, will
grow naturally over time, helping to minimize the velocity of
waves, Sykes said.
</P>
<P>
   Built to standards set by the Federal Emergency Management
Agency, or FEMA, the building's lowest horizontal structure will be
14 feet above sea level.
</P>
<P>
   Its sides will be made of high-strength tensile fabric suspended
from five giant steel girders that form the vaulted roof of the
center.
</P>
<P>
   Sykes won't guarantee that the building is invincible, but he's
confident it will stand.
</P>
<P>
   ''The beach is getting bigger, it satisfies all the FEMA
requirements, it's consistent with the pier development philosophy,
it fronts on the busiest, most popular street in town - the
Boardwalk - it has uninterrupted services from the street and it's
surrounded by dunes,'' he said Wednesday, while giving a tour of
the site.
</P>
<P>
   ''You could have two feet of water in the streets of Wildwood,
and this building will still be dry,'' Sykes said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Duane Sloan says that in the event of a catastrophic
storm, Wildwood will have bigger problems than a wet convention
center.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the concern is a storm, and the water were to get to the
height of the Boardwalk, the entire island would be underwater.
It'd be a disaster area anyway. I've never known the water to get
as high as the planking. If it's only under the Boardwalk, it's
only going to be under the convention center.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Totah, a marine biologist who lives near the convention
center site, says it should have been built downtown, to spur
development in rundown parts of Wildwood.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic access and limited public parking around the site will
hamper its effectiveness, Totah said.
</P>
<P>
   ''To me, the convention center will stand as a monument to how
the system failed, to government stupidity. Certain people thought
it would look good on the beach. It's not helping the town and it
goes against everything we should be doing on our beaches,'' Totah
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jo Hall, a professor of marine and geological sciences at
Rider University, calls the plan ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's stupid. It's ludicrous,'' she said. ''It might last 50
years, but we might get a major storm before that. In that case,
the water will wash the sand right out from under it and you'll
have this thing sticking up out of the water, like the bunker in
Cape May Point,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   To the Sports Authority, the location is what will make the
building a success.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're using that as the major selling point for conferences
and whatnot,'' said authority spokesman Daniel Emmer. ''You can't
duplicate the fact that you can walk outside and be right on the
beach. That's what's selling the building.''
</P>
<P>
   -
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Sports Authority: http://www.njsea.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
