<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior citizen home owners indicted for alleged neglect  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The state closed a Waldwick home for the
elderly Friday, a day after its owners were indicted for the
alleged neglect of a senior citizen in their Rockland County, N.Y.,
boarding home.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Department of Health and Senior Services removed
the final three residents from the Shannon House Rest Home on
Friday, citing a lack of supervision because the owners were in the
Rockland County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   The Montvale couple, Maureen and Michael Culhane, were charged
Thursday with locking an 87-year-old woman in a room in their Pearl
River, N.Y., boarding home.
</P>
<P>
   A week earlier, New Jersey investigators shut down another of
their boarding homes for the elderly, the Hillas Vale Guest Lodge
in Montvale, because of allegedly unsanitary conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The Culhanes, who have pleaded not guilty to the New York
charges, were still being held Saturday on $25,000 bail each.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the 18-bed Waldwick home, where new admissions
had been banned by the state for months while it was under state
investigation, was in better condition than the Hillas Vale.
</P>
<P>
   The Culhanes could face state penalties in the Waldwick case.
They also face $10,000 fine from the state Department of Community
Affairs for refusing to allow inspectors in enter the Montvale
boarding home.
</P>
<P>
   The Bergen County Prosecutor's Office has said it will
investigate possible charges stemming from the conditions in
Montvale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-22-00 1328 </TRAILER>
