<DOCNO> APW20000722.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One week after slur flap, first lady visits LI synagogue  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTHAMPTON BEACH, N.Y. (AP) - Seeking to calm jittery Jewish
voters, Hillary Rodham Clinton appeared Saturday at an Orthodox
synagogue to denounce terrorism against Israel and support its
right to be free from violence.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady spoke before an overflow crowd of about 350
people just one week after her campaign was rocked by an allegation
that she made an anti-Semitic remark in 1974. She has angrily
denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know this has been a very difficult and trying week for
you,'' said Rabbi Marc Schneier, who invited and introduced
Clinton. ''It's time for us to move on. Hillary has always been a
friend of our people.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke about the ongoing Camp David peace talks, telling
her audience that ''the challenges the president and prime minister
are facing are rooted in whether or not others will give up their
hatred and their sense of violence ... in return for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat have been meeting at Camp David in
efforts to reach a new Middle East peace agreement. The president,
who was in Japan for an economic summit, is due back at the talks
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady spoke at the Hampton Synagogue in Westhampton
Beach, an exclusive Long Island summer resort. Though nominally
Orthodox, the synagogue attracts a cross-section of Jewish
worshippers.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP Senate candidate, U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio, was scheduled to
speak at the synagogue next Saturday. Both candidates are courting
the Jewish voters who make up 12 percent of the New York
electorate.
</P>
<P>
   During the service, as dictated by religious custom, Mrs.
Clinton sat on the side of the synagogue reserved for women. She
was accompanied by a female Secret Service agent and Schneier's
wife, Toby.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton visit came one week after the first published
reports regarding her alleged use of an anti-Semitic remark toward
an Arkansas campaign worker in 1974. The charge appeared in ''State
of a Union,'' a new book by former National Enquirer reporter Jerry
Oppenheimer.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, in an emotional news conference, emphatically
denied the allegation. Traditional wisdom says Mrs. Clinton needs
to win 60 percent of the Jewish vote for a November victory; she is
currently polling between 50 and 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   During her appearance at the synagogue, Mrs. Clinton never
mentioned Arafat or the PLO. Instead, she focused on Barak and
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis, she said, have a right ''to keep their children
safe from violence and terrorism. We know in our hearts that God
has deemed their cause just ... I believe we have to support their
efforts, and particularly support what the prime minister is going
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   She later told the audience, ''We should rededicate ourselves to
standing against bigotry, prejudice, racism and anti-Semitism.''
But some in the audience remained unconvinced about Mrs. Clinton's
commitment to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone likes her very much,'' said temple treasurer Seymour
Siegel. ''They're just disturbed about her passion with the PLO and
her history with those causes.''
</P>
<P>
   He was apparently referring to the first lady's embrace of
Arafat's wife, Soha, after she had made a speech accusing Israeli
troops of using poison gas on Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Worshipper Amy Gross disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought she was wonderful,'' Gross said. ''I thought she's
truly hoping for the same peace we all are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-22-00 1334 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000722.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> RETRANSIMITTING to add photo line  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTHAMPTON BEACH, N.Y. (AP) - Seeking to calm jittery Jewish
voters, Hillary Rodham Clinton appeared Saturday at an Orthodox
synagogue to denounce terrorism against Israel and support its
right to be free from violence.
</P>
<P>
