<HEADLINE> Contest Winner Parodies Faulkner  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, Miss. (AP) -- ''You hear the master behind the levity,''
the organizer of the 11th annual Faux Faulkner writealike contest
says of this year's winner.
</P>
<P>
   But Catherine Dupree, 27, who won top honors, says if master
storyteller William Faulkner were alive he'd probably be appalled
by those parodying his writing style.
</P>
<P>
   Dupree's winning entry was about a deep-fried Dixie diet that
proliferates ''clumps of cellulite and folds of fat.'' The satire
is about a character in a fast food drive-thru line considering
whether to add french fries to her order.
</P>
<P>
   The inspiration for the piece, Dupree said, wasn't Faulker, but
''Southern obsession with fried food.''
</P>
<P>
   Dupree, who will attend graduate school in journalism this fall
in her home state of Massachusetts, will read her entry Sunday at a
ceremony on the front lawn of Faulkner's home in Oxford.
</P>
</TEXT>
