<HEADLINE> Bonnie Raitt Hopes To Inspire Kids  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Bonnie Raitt was 14 when somebody handed her
a copy of the recording ''Blues at Newport 1963,'' all but
instantly transforming her from '60s folk-rock aficionado to blues
fanatic.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was catapulted into a level of fandom that I've never
recovered from,'' the Grammy-winning guitarist said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six years later, Raitt, 50, is hoping to work the same
kind of epiphany on 200 other impressionable young minds. Only this
time she'll be the teacher when she plays host to a world
music-blues workshop for inner-city students from the Hollywood
Bowl on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   If it isn't enough to infuse students with an appreciation of
the music Raitt calls ''the most important cultural contribution
America's ever made,'' she hopes a star-studded concert will be.
The students will be invited to stick around afterward to hear
Raitt, Alvin Youngblood Hart, KoKo Taylor and others perform.
</P>
</TEXT>
