<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hartford minister facing prostitution charges was banned from jails </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - A minister and prominent police critic,
now accused of promoting prostitution, had been banned from
visiting state prisons after a female inmate accused him of
inappropriate behavior, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Henry L. Price has been banned from the state's jails
since November, Department of Correction spokeswoman Christina
Polce said Friday. Polce said the prisoner accused Price of
''inappropriate behavior and activities'' during a visit.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of that allegation, which led to a four-month
investigation by correction officials, was not available Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Price had a contract to counsel inmates with the correction
department because of his job as manager of the family
reunification program of Community Partners in Action.
</P>
<P>
   But prison officials never called him back to do work, Polce
said. The state investigation of Price concluded in March, and his
status as a volunteer and the contract provider for Community
Partners in Action was revoked, Polce said.
</P>
<P>
   Polce said the correction department's investigation had nothing
to do with the Hartford Police Department's probe of allegations
that Price was working as a pimp.
</P>
<P>
   Price surrendered to police on Wednesday and was charged with
one count of promoting prostitution, one count of second-degree
prostitution and one count of third-degree assault.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest warrant was immediately sealed by a Hartford Superior
Court judge, meaning the state's case against Price is closed to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   Price is due in court Aug. 2. He is free on $150,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   The Hartford Courant, citing police sources, reported that women
who were counseled in prison by Price have accused him of setting
them up in apartments, renting them cars and getting them jobs as
prostitutes after their release.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for his help, the women allegedly told police, they
had to pay him 75 percent of the money they made as hookers.
</P>
<P>
   Through his attorney, Price denies being a pimp, and he alleges
through his friends and allies that the police may have set him up.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Price being banned from the prisons, Price's
attorney, Salvatore Bonanno said, ''His volunteer privileges were
suspended when he and his wife went to a prison on a personal
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''The suspension is only connected to abusing a volunteer
pass,'' he said. ''It's my understanding it is not connected to the
prostitution charges against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonanno declined to describe exactly what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Price, a former president of the Greater Hartford African
American Alliance who turned his life around after a murder
conviction, was among the leaders of a group that picketed weekly
outside the police department for months after Officer Robert C.
Allan shot and killed Aquan Salmon, a 14-year-old robbery suspect,
in April 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
