<HEADLINE> Precautions for mosquitoes, spraying  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   The state Department of Environmental Protection
offers the
following precautions to minimize the risk of exposure to the West
Nile-like strain of the encephalitis virus:
<TEXT>
<P>
   - Minimize time outdoors between dusk and dawn, when mosquitoes
are most active.
</P>
<P>
   - Be sure door and window screens are tight-fitting and in good
repair.
</P>
<P>
   - Wear shoes, socks, long pants and a long-sleeved shirt when
outdoors for long periods of time or when mosquitoes are most
active. Clothing should be light-colored and made of tightly woven
materials.
</P>
<P>
   - Use mosquito netting when sleeping outdoors or in an
unscreened structure and to protect small babies when outside.
</P>
<P>
   -Eliminate any standing water, including in unattended swimming
pools, where mosquitoes breed.
</P>
<P>
   -Use mosquito repellant with DEET.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   For residents of areas where spraying will take place, the DEP
advises:
</P>
<P>
   - Remain indoors with the windows closed and air conditioning
turned off during spraying and for three to four hours after,
whenever possible. It is safe to go outside for short periods of
time immediately after spraying.
</P>
<P>
   - If you must remain outside, avoid eye contact with the spray.
Rinse immediately with water or eye drops if contact is made.
</P>
<P>
   - Do not allow children to play in areas still wet from
spraying.
</P>
<P>
   - Wash exposed skin with soap and water.
</P>
<P>
   - If driving during spraying, close your car windows and vents.
</P>
<P>
   - Bring pets inside.
</P>
<P>
   -Bring laundry and toys inside before spraying and wash them
with soap and water if exposed to pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   - Cover outdoor tables and play equipment or rinse them with
water after spraying.
</P>
<P>
   - Cover swimming pools when possible.
</P>
<P>
   - Wash any exposed fruits or vegetables with water before using.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call the DEP Mosquito Information Line at
(860) 424-4184 for a recorded message, the Department of Public
Health at (860) 509-7994 or your local health department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-22-00 1346 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000722.0062 </DOCNO>
