<HEADLINE> Spielberg Kin Impersonator Sentenced  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) -- Jonathan Taylor Spielberg, who enrolled in a
Catholic high school pretending to be a nephew of the famous
filmmaker, has been sentenced to two years' probation for forgery.
</P>
<P>
   He got an 11-month suspended jail sentence on Friday and was
ordered to receive mental health counseling, perform 100 hours of
community service and avoid contact with anyone under age 18.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg is about 27 years old, although his attorney said
Spielberg's exact date of birth is uncertain. He was born
Anoushirvan D. Fakhran in Iran, but changed his name 2&AMP;frac12; years ago.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, he attended high school classes in
Fairfax, claiming to be a 14-year-old freshman.
</P>
<P>
   He drove a BMW with ''SPLBERG'' license plates that he parked in
the principal's spot. The school received a fictitious transcript
from the ''Beverly Hills Private School for Actors,'' listing
stellar grades.
</P>
<P>
   School officials discovered the ruse when they tried to contact
Steven Spielberg about Jonathan's absenteeism. The call was routed
to Steven Spielberg's security consultants in Los Angeles, who
alerted Fairfax City police.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg has said he enrolled in high school ''just for the
fun, to get the experience I never had.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
