<HEADLINE> Novelist John le Carre Donates Land  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Novelist John le Carre has given a stretch of
Cornish coastline to the National Trust to keep it ''out of the
reach of human predators.''
</P>
<P>
   The 68-year-old author, whose real name is David Cornwell,
bought a cottage on rugged cliffs in southwest England 30 years ago
with the proceeds of his book ''The Spy Who Came in from the
Cold,'' an early best seller in a string of hit spy novels.
</P>
<P>
   Below the isolated cottage is half a mile of coastline that le
Carre is turning over to the trust, a charity that cares for
historic buildings and areas of natural beauty around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope many more landowners will join me in putting precious
coast land for all time out of the reach of human predators,'' le
Carre said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The monetary value of land was not made known, but the National
Trust described it as ''a generous donation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
