<HEADLINE> Fanwood bike thief 'trades up'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FANWOOD, N.J. (AP) - Someone is stealing bicycles here and
leaving old ones in their place.
</P>
<P>
   Police say at least four times in the past month - and three
times last year - a thief has made off with a shiny new bike, and
left a beat-up old one in its place.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he didn't ride it, he pushed it,'' said Detective Eugene
Chin.
</P>
<P>
   The stolen bikes ranged in price from $150 to $380. The ones
left in their place were worth maybe $50, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police in other towns say they've also seen this trick.
</P>
<P>
   ''They use an old bike for transportation,'' said Roselle Park
Sgt. Paul Morrison. ''When they get here, they get a better bike.''
</P>
<P>
   In each of the Fanwood thefts, bicycles were taken from outside
houses or from unlocked garages.
</P>
<P>
   Ten-year-old Beua Lia had his new bike swiped from outside his
house. He saved for months to be able to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the first time in his life, he decided to spring for
something that was a major purchase with his own money,'' the boy's
father, Peter Lia, told The Star-Ledger of Newark for Saturday's
editions. ''He's only had the bike four or five weeks. He really
feels terrible about the thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He might feel even worse about the bike the thief left behind
for him: a baby-blue girl's bike, with white handlebars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
