<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pessimism Over Ending Sri Lanka War  </HEADLINE>
By NAMINI WIJEDASA
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- Minority Tamil and Muslim parties in
Sri Lanka said Saturday they no longer have any hope that the
government and opposition will agree to constitutional changes
aimed at ending the island nation's 17-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
   The Tamil Tiger insurgents, charging discrimination by the
Sinhalese majority, have been fighting since 1983 in an effort to
carve out a Tamil homeland in the northern and eastern portions of
the country. The fighting has killed 62,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The government of President Chandrika Kumaratunga and the main
opposition United National Party have been trying to reach an
accord on clauses to give more autonomy to provinces in a bid to
end the ethnic conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The plan has already been rejected by the Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam rebels, who say they will settle for nothing less than
a homeland. But even if the Tamil rebels change their minds, the
plan would be a nonstarter if the opposition party rejects the
government proposals aimed at ending the ethnic conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Four months of dialogue suffered a setback Friday when
opposition leader Ranil Wickremesinghe stormed out of a meeting
with the government.
</P>
<P>
   Wickremesinghe accused the government of carrying out a smear
campaign against him trying to link him with the Tamil rebels, and
he told Kumaratunga he would boycott future discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we will virtually have to bid goodbye to bipartisan
talks,'' said Rauf Hakeem, secretary of the Sri Lanka Muslim
Congress party.
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem said only the minority Tamil and Muslim parties can put
the talks back on track by acting as conduit between the government
and opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ''Wickremesinghe's threatened boycott is a big, big setback,''
said Dharmalingam Sidharthan, leader of the People's Liberation
Organization of Tamil Eelam, a former rebel group that renounced
violence and joined the political mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the present context, everything seems to be going for a
six,'' agreed Veerasingham Anandasangaree, vice president of the
mainstream Tamil political party, the Tamil United Liberation
Front, using a cricket term for everything going haywire.
</P>
<P>
   Kumaratunga's hope to end the war with Tamil Tiger rebels hit
another snag Friday when Sri Lanka's powerful Buddhist monks said
they oppose the government's proposed constitutional changes.
</P>
<P>
   Although the country's Buddhist clergy generally preach
nonviolence, they have urged the government to carry on its war
against Tamil militants. They say the country's minority Tamils,
who are mostly Hindus, should not be given any special privileges.
</P>
<P>
   The monks said Friday they would oppose the government's
proposed draft constitution because it makes too many concessions
to the Tamils. The government's proposed amendments would grant
wide powers to regional authorities, apparently in an attempt to
influence the 3.2 million Tamils.
</P>
<P>
   The government initially hoped to submit the draft constitution
to parliament before the session ends Aug. 24, but this is now
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tamil Tiger rebels continued sporadic attacks in the
country's north, wounding three soldiers, government spokesman
Ariya Rubasinghe said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He said the soldiers were wounded Friday by rebel mortar fire in
Nargarkovil and Meesalai-South northeast of Jaffna city, the
rebels' former stronghold which they are trying to recapture.
</P>
<P>
   Rubasinghe said two rebels were killed Friday by soldiers at
Ariyalai in the Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-22-00 1448 </TRAILER>
