<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Hostages May Be Let Go  </HEADLINE>
By JIM GOMEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) -- Three Malaysians and two Filipinos
kidnapped by guerillas from a diving resort three months ago are
likely to be released soon, government negotiators said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The five have been held by Abu Sayyaf rebels on Jolo island
since being abducted in a group of 21 people from Malaysia's
Sipadan resort.
</P>
<P>
   Six other Malaysians and one German woman in the group have been
freed.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators said rebel leaders were apparently debating how to
divide hundreds of thousands of dollars in ransom. Their release is
now ''in the works,'' chief negotiator Robert Aventajado said.
</P>
<P>
   The release of the five would leave nine still in captivity:
seven Europeans and two South Africans.
</P>
<P>
   The same rebel band has kidnapped dozens of others, usually
holding the victims for ransom.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the rebel band abducted 50 teachers and students from
two schools on nearby Basilan island.
</P>
<P>
   Aventajado earlier presented two teachers released Friday by the
rebels -- the last of the 50 to be freed.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers, Erlinda Manuel and Teresita Academia, wept when
they saw their families. ''It was a bitter experience,'' Manuel
said of their captivity.
</P>
<P>
   They survived a military assault on the main Abu Sayyaf
stronghold and weeks of flight through the jungle with the rebels
to escape pursuing troops.
</P>
<P>
   ''I won't say anything about the rebels,'' said Academia's
husband, Romeo, also a teacher. ''The important thing is my wife is
back.''
</P>
<P>
   At one time Academia wrote her husband asking him to raise
$5,600 for her release, her husband said.
</P>
<P>
   ''But it's impossible to raise that on a teacher's salary, so I
decided to wait and see what happened with the government
negotiations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf consists of several hundred heavily armed rebels
divided into several bands led by at least five commanders. The
group has been accused of banditry, kidnappings and numerous
attacks on Christians.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Sipadan diving resort abduction, the Abu Sayyaf has
also abducted several other people.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the remaining hostages consist of six French, three
Germans, two Finns, two South Africans, 15 Filipinos and three
Malaysians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
