<HEADLINE> Fugitive wanted for 1991 Tarrytown shooting caught in Panama  </HEADLINE>
By RACHEL LA CORTE
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) - A man who had been a fugitive since his 1991
indictment for fatally shooting his estranged wife in New York was
caught in Central America and brought back to the United States on
Saturday, according to the U.S. Marshals Service.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Grullon was caught in Panama at about 6 p.m. EDT Friday
by U.S. Marshals, U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service and
Panamanian Fugitive Squad and has been brought to Miami, said
Deputy U.S. Marshal John D. Amat.
</P>
<P>
   ''Based on leads provided by the Dominican National Police, he
was tracked to Panama,'' Amat said.
</P>
<P>
   Grullon was turned over to the Miami-Dade Police warrant squad,
Amat said.
</P>
<P>
   Miami-Dade Police did not immediately return an Associated Press
phone call Saturday, but Amat said it was likely that Grullon would
appear in court in Miami, possibly Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Grullon was flown to Miami because there was not a direct flight
to New York, Amat said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's here now, he's on our soil,'' said Detective Sgt. Gene
Buonanno of the Tarrytown Police Department, the agency leading the
New York investigation. ''Now he's mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Grullon was indicted by a grand jury in Westchester County in
December 1991 on charges he killed his estranged wife, Yolina
Camacho. Police say Grullon shot Camacho in front of several
witnesses, including the couple's two young children in the
basement of the Hilton. Camacho worked there as a housekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Grullon fled to the Dominican Republic. He was arrested and
spent several months in jail there before being released on bail
and disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's been spitting in my face for many years,'' said Buonanno,
who described the international legal process of the last years as
''nothing but a fiasco.''
</P>
<P>
   Buonanno enlisted the help of U.S. Rep. Benjamin Gilman to put
pressure on the Dominican Republic to extradite Grullon and another
man, Pablo Almonte, who is wanted for the 1988 slaying of a New
York City cop. Almonte is still at large.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman, a Republican from Middletown who is the head of the
International Relations Committee in the House of Representatives,
barred the transfer of millions of dollars in aid money and
equipment to pressure the country.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE - Associated Press writer Deepti Hajela in New
York contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
