<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reality TV Rewarding for CBS  </HEADLINE>
By LYNN ELBER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- CBS executives on Saturday defended
''Big Brother,'' the network's exercise in voyeurism, while
acknowledging the unpredictability of putting private lives on
television.
</P>
<P>
   ''Would I do it again? In a second,'' Leslie Moonves, CBS
Television president and chief executive officer, said of the
program that has sequestered 10 strangers in a camera-filled house
for three months.
</P>
<P>
   ''Big Brother'' and the hit ''Survivor'' reflect CBS' effort to
remove the ''closed for the summer sign'' and offer viewers more
than ''Diagnosis Murder'' reruns, Moonves said.
</P>
<P>
   CBS' reward has been a bigger audience, particularly among the
younger viewers advertisers pay more to reach, and the excitement
of having ''water-cooler'' shows that get people talking, Moonves
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some 30-second commercial spots on the ''Survivor'' finale in
August will fetch as much as $600,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the Television Critics Association, Moonves was
peppered with questions about the ethics and ramifications of using
real people for entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Politics unexpectedly entered the ''Big Brother'' house with
William Collins, reported to be a follower of former Nation of
Islam leader Khalid Abdul Muhammad. Muhammad was ousted from the
Nation of Islam for calling Jews ''bloodsuckers.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Collins became the first contestant ousted by
fellow house members and viewers. He said during a follow-up
interview on the show that he had been a member of the New Black
Panther Party for Self-Defense, of which Muhammad is national
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very tough finding out everything in everybody's
background,'' Moonves said. ''I would have done a lot more
investigating.''
</P>
<P>
   The network spent $100,000 on background checks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moonves declined to say if Collins would have been allowed on
the show if he remained an active party member. Moonves and CBS
Entertainment President Nancy Tellem said Collins espoused no hate
or political messages during his time on ''Big Brother'' and that
none would be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS executives also were questioned about the wisdom of
allowing ''Big Brother'' contestant Karen to use TV -- with her
children probably watching -- to criticize her husband and marriage.
The network withheld contestant's full names.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it didn't happen on the air'' her marital problems likely
would have emerged anyway, Moonves said, adding that he did share
others' concerns about how Karen's children might be affected.
</P>
<P>
   But the contestants signed up voluntarily and were made fully
aware of the scrutiny they would face, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have nothing to apologize for,'' he said of CBS' reality
programs.
</P>
<P>
   There's already a sequel planned for ''Survivor,'' which
stranded 16 contestants on an island for a $1 million prize, and
CBS plans a big kick-off for the new show.
</P>
<P>
   ''Survivor II: The Australian Outback'' will debut immediately
after the Super Bowl on Jan. 28. The current ''Survivor'' will go
out with a bang Aug. 23: The two-hour finale will be followed by a
live ''town hall'' meeting with the contestants.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Internet leaks, CBS will wait to post the names of
ousted ''Survivor'' contestants until after the weekly show airs.
Moonves declined to comment on Web sites claiming to know the
winner's identity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-22-00 1701 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
