<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mourners Decry Italy Teen's Killing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPLES, Italy (AP) -- Angry mourners filled a Naples cathedral
Saturday for the funeral of a teen-age scooter driver who was shot
and killed for running a police checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Castellano, 17, ran the checkpoint because he wasn't
wearing a helmet and didn't want to be ticketed. He had been
ticketed repeatedly before Thursday's shooting for flouting a March
law that mandates helmets for Italy's 9 million scooter and
motorcycle drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager reportedly loathed helmets because they flattened
his gel-held hairdo.
</P>
<P>
   Mario's aunt stood before his casket Saturday in front of 1,500
mourners to urge an end to a protest boycott on helmet-wearing by
Naples' young.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anyone who wants to show respect for Mario instead should put
on their helmets, and they should do it for him,'' said the aunt,
identified only as Edda. ''They should put them on and keep them on
even more than before.''
</P>
<P>
   The nights since the killing have been marked by vigils and
scattered riots, with young people both placing flowers and
smashing car windows and overturning police vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Minister Enzo Bianco called the shooting unjustifiable
and promised to bring the circumstances of the case to light.
</P>
<P>
   Naples Police Chief Nicola Izza expressed regret but said gang
wars had made the city's police particularly ''tense'' lately, and
police complained that Neapolitans increasingly were ignoring the
helmet law despite increased checks and public-awareness campaigns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
