<HEADLINE> Four more birds test positive for West Nile virus in Westchester  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. (AP) - Four more birds have tested positive
for the West Nile virus in Westchester County, the county health
department said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The birds included three Blue Jays found in Somers, Rye and
Scarsdale and a crow found in Purchase, the health department said.
</P>
<P>
   The department announced plans to begin spraying for mosquitoes
in the communities surrounding the areas where the birds were
found.
</P>
<P>
   The plans call for spraying to tentatively begin on Tuesday in
areas surrounding Yonkers, Greenburgh, Ardsley, White Plains, Rye,
Harrison, Mamaroneck, North Salem, and Somers.
</P>
<P>
   Trucks will spray the pesticide Anvil, the health department
said.
</P>
<P>
   The West Nile virus first appeared in the Western Hemisphere
last summer, killing seven people in the New York area and
infecting 62 others. The outbreak prompted a massive campaign of
aerial and ground spraying.
</P>
</TEXT>
