<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mideast Peace Talks in Low Gear  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- The Middle East summit is in low gear in
deference to the Jewish Sabbath, but negotiations are going on,
quietly and informally, as Israeli and Palestinian leaders await
President Clinton's return.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional Jews devote Saturday to prayer and rest; secular
Israelis normally do neither. But it could be politically unwise
for an Israeli official to conduct normal business on that day.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, discussions were apt to be quiet at the Camp David
presidential retreat as the summit passed through a slow period
until sundown.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, attending an economic summit in Japan, trimmed his
schedule so he could return to the Camp David talks by Sunday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said the president was
briefed on the status of the talks while en route to a meeting
Saturday morning (Friday night EDT) with Japanese Prime Minister
Yoshiro Mori, and ''his intention is to get back to Camp David as
soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They have continued their discussions, but there are some
things the leaders have to do among themselves,'' Lockhart said.
''I expect him to get right back to work when he gets there.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is acting as host in
Clinton's absence.
</P>
<P>
   ''In our view, the parties are making serious efforts,'' State
Department spokesman Richard Boucher said Friday, before the onset
of the Sabbath. ''But nonetheless, it is hard going.''
</P>
<P>
   Deliberations remained shrouded in the secrecy that has marked
the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher provided scant information before a ''lid'' was clamped
on public statements until Sunday morning. He said some news
reports of summit proceedings have been accurate, but most were
not.
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem, two Israeli officials disclosed Friday that the
United States was promoting an Israeli-initiated proposal to
recognize Palestinian administrative control over Arab
neighborhoods of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The aim was to clear the most stubborn obstacle to a Camp David
peace agreement, deep differences on Jerusalem's future.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Melchior, a rabbi who is a member of Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak's cabinet, said the proposal conveyed the
''characteristic'' of Palestinian sovereignty in the eastern area
of the contested city, a long-cherished Palestinian goal.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting coolly to the ideas, Hassan Abdel Rahman, Washington
representative of the Palestine Liberation Organization, said:
''Short of total Palestinian sovereignty over East Jerusalem, there
is not a ground for an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Rahman told The Associated Press by telephone he could not
verify that such a proposal had been put on the table at secluded
Camp David, where the summit was in its 11th day.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat is demanding sovereignty over
East Jerusalem, the city's older area that Israel captured from
Jordanian troops in the 1967 Six-Day War. He envisions it as the
capital of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has vowed to keep Jerusalem a united city.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has refused to recognize Jerusalem as Israel's
capital, although Clinton promised that recognition in his campaign
for the White House eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Then-Secretary of State James A. Baker III told the Palestinians
in 1991 that Israel's annexation of East Jerusalem was invalid,
Rahman recalled, ''and I have not heard the United States had
changed its position.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the current plan, Palestinian areas outside the city also
would be placed under Palestinian administrative control.
</P>
<P>
   ''These villages are not really ours,'' Israeli Justice Minister
Yossi Beilin told Israel army radio. ''We must not allow this
mirage to become an obstruction to Ehud Barak to arrive at the
dream of peace with the Palestinians, now so close.''
</P>
<P>
   Melchior said the plan would give the Palestinians some
''symbols of sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   He said later through an aide that this characterization was his
own and did not emerge from the talks at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: State Department Mideast Summit site:
http://www.state.gov/www/regions/nea/cdavid--summit.html
</P>
</TEXT>
