<HEADLINE> Court: Spain Owns Sunken Warships  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Spain owns the remains of two warships that
sank off the Virginia coast two centuries ago, a federal appeals
court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed a judge's ruling
last year granting Spain title to the Juno, which disappeared off
the Eastern Shore in 1802 with about 435 passengers aboard.
According to some accounts, the ship was laden with as much as $500
million in coins and precious metals.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court also reversed a judge's ruling on a second
ship, La Galga. The judge had ruled that the ship, which sank in
1750 a few miles north of what is believed to be the Juno site,
belonged to Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Spain appealed the decision and now owns both shipwrecks, even
though they are well within the three-mile limit that Congress
established as territorial waters for coastal states.
</P>
<P>
   The court based its decision on a 1902 treaty between Spain and
the United States, saying the pact is ''essential to protecting
United States shipwrecks and military gravesites'' in other parts
of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The company Sea Hunt had salvage rights to the ships. Ben
Benson, president of the company, said he has spent about $2
million on the project -- much of it on legal fees. Benson said he
and state officials will discuss whether to appeal Friday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Spain's claims of ownership of the ships are the first the
country has made in hundreds of years of losing ships in nearby
waters.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now, it looks like we have Spanish enclaves dotting our
shore,'' said Anthony F. Troy, a former Virginia attorney general
who represented Benson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
