<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State officials urge calm after virus discovery  </HEADLINE>
syfonsstmho
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) - State officials on Saturday urged people
not to panic as they made plans to spray against an outbreak of the
West Nile-like strain of the encephalitis virus.
</P>
<P>
   Infected mosquitoes have been discovered in Stamford, the first
sign of the virus this year in Connecticut. As a result, the state
Department of Environmental Protection will spray in the towns of
Stamford, Darien and New Canaan Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the spraying, combined with routine precautions
against mosquitoes, should minimize the risk any humans will
contract the virus.
</P>
<P>
   ''We anticipated finding the virus because it's been found all
around the region,'' DEP spokeswoman Michele Sullivan said
Saturday. Mosquitoes and birds have tested positive for the virus
in New York and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ''The spraying is just to reduce the mosquito population and try
to reduce the ramifications of the virus,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stamford mosquitoes, trapped at Sleepy Hollow Park in the
Springdale section July 11, primarily bite birds but have been
known to bite humans, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   No human cases of the virus have ever been confirmed in
Connecticut. Last year, the virus sickened 62 New Yorkers, killing
seven but it has not been detected in humans this year.
</P>
<P>
   The virus is most dangerous for children under 5, the elderly
and people with weakened immune systems. Otherwise, it causes
flu-like symptoms in healthy adults.
</P>
<P>
   The DEP will spray the pesticide Resmethrin from canisters
mounted on trucks - the same method used last year after the
outbreak in lower Fairfield County. The spraying will begin around
sunset and take up to six hours to complete.
</P>
<P>
   Spraying will take place in the eastern half of Stamford,
between the Merritt Parkway and Interstate 95; the western half of
Darien from I-95 to the New Canaan line; and the southwestern
portion of New Canaan from the Darien/Stamford lines to the Merritt
Parkway.
</P>
<P>
   The area comprises a two-mile radius from Sleepy Hollow Park. If
it rains, the spraying will have to be postponed.
</P>
<P>
   A group calling themselves ''Connecticut Safe,'' held a meeting
in Stamford Saturday to express opposition to the spraying. Rivka
Lieber said they consider the risk of becoming ill from the
pesticide to be greater than the risk of contracting the virus from
mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want safer solutions,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stamford Health Director Anthony Iton said such concerns are
unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm no fan of pesticides,'' he said. ''I think in general
they're used without appropriate discretion and they are not used
in a targeted manner. This particular application is a targeted,
rational and prudent use of these pesticides.''
</P>
<P>
   Stamford Mayor Dannel Malloy, who was critical of the state's
response to the virus last year, said officials were doing a better
job this season.
</P>
<P>
   Mosquitoes have been trapped weekly at 73 sites around the state
since June 1, tested for both West Nile and Eastern Equine
Encephalitis. More than 90 dead birds have been tested for the
virus. The state has distributed $500,000 to aid municipalities'
anti-mosquito programs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all prevention efforts, however, Malloy said the virus
shows no signs of disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I expect we're going to be dealing with this disease for at
least a few years,'' Malloy said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-22-00 1827 </TRAILER>
