<HEADLINE> Russian Positions Under Chechen Fire  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia (AP) -- Independence fighters mounted a series of
hit-and run attacks on Russian troops in Chechnya, lobbing shells
on Russian posts in the capital of Grozny and detonating a mine
under a truck carrying soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The truck struck the mine on Saturday near Noviye Atagi, about
six miles south of Grozny, military officials said. The Interior
Ministry press center said that there were casualties, but did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   No casualties were reported after guerillas shelled Russian
positions in Chechnya 10 times in 24 hours starting Friday night,
including eight attacks in Grozny, the Russian military command
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials estimate that about 500 rebels remain in
Grozny, despite the taking of the city by federal forces in
February when most of the guerrillas fled the city.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow has insisted for months that the rebels are on the verge
of defeat, but the separatists have turned to sniping, car bombs
and remote-control land mines to show they can still inflict harm
on Russian positions in the breakaway republic.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, four Interior Ministry soldiers were killed and three
others injured when their truck was blown up by a mine in the Shali
region south of Grozny, the news agency Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
   Russian forces also tried to keep up the pressure on the rebels
on Saturday, sending Su-25 attack planes and helicopter gunships on
sorties against the Argun gorge, a key rebel refuge and supply
route in the mountainous southern part of the republic.
</P>
<P>
   Russian ground troops scoured forests for rebels near the
settlements of Samashki and Zakan Yurt west of Grozny, the military
command said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian units on the border with the neighboring region of
Dagestan have been put on alert because of the upsurge in rebel
attacks, officials said. The past several days have seen a spate of
ambushes in which at least 10 Russian soldiers were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials say that the rebels have stepped up their
attacks to embarrass Russian President Vladimir Putin during the
Group of Eight summit in Okinawa, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops were driven out of Chechnya in a 1994-96 war with
independence fighters, and Moscow lost control of the region.
Troops returned in September after militants based in Chechnya
attacked villages in Dagestan, and after about 300 people died in
apartment bombings the government blames on Chechens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
