<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reds Expect Larkin To Reject Trade  </HEADLINE>
By JOE KAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- Barry Larkin is getting tugged on from all
sides as he makes the biggest decision of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati Reds fans urged him to stay Saturday, giving the
All-Star shortstop an emotion-stirring ovation. The Mets lobbied
him by phone to accept a trade to New York to strengthen them for a
playoff chase.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the commotion, Reds general manager Jim Bowden
predicted Larkin will reject a trade to the Mets and finish the
season in Cincinnati. Bowden urged his team captain to make up his
mind fast.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's up to Larkin, who will decide whether to approve the
trade to New York for three players, whose identity has not been
revealed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an emotional roller coaster,'' Larkin said following a
7-3 victory over Arizona. ''I actually thought I might not be here
today, but I am.''
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner's office gave the Mets permission to negotiate
with Larkin during a 72-hour window that started at 10 a.m.
Saturday. It probably won't take that long.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets want Larkin to fill in for shortstop Rey Ordonez, out
the rest of the season with a broken arm. Larkin has indicated he's
not interested going to a team for a half-season, preferring a
contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Larkin was noncommittal before learning about the Mets' plans
first-hand.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's something my agent (Eric Goldschmidt) and I have to
talk about, my family as well,'' Larkin said. ''It's not cast in
stone. We have to wait and see what's on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Mets general manager Steve Phillips spoke with Goldschmidt
several times during the game. Phillips expects to have a good idea
of whether the trade will go through by midday Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would take whatever Barry is willing to give us the last two
months,'' Phillips said. ''I understand that he's from Cincinnati
and it would be tough to live out of a suitcase for two months. In
the end, it comes down to whether he gets a contract extension or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Reds general manager is convinced Larkin will
veto the trade. Bowden urged the two sides to reach a decision
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds arranged the trade after rejecting Larkin's request for
a three-year, $27.9 million extension. Larkin can become a free
agent after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ''As of now, the Mets have told me they are not willing to sign
him for $27.9 million,'' Bowden said. ''Barry and his agent have
informed us if they don't sign him for $27.9 million, then he's
going to reject the trade. So based on what I'm hearing, I think at
some point it gets rejected.''
</P>
<P>
   If the trade is rejected, Larkin will finish the season in
Cincinnati, Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he rejects the deal, there will be no other deals,'' Bowden
said. ''This is it.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin is holding out hope that he can work out an extension
with the Reds that will allow him to finish his career in
Cincinnati. His hometown let him know how it feels about him
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   There were numerous pro-Larkin banners in the stadium and he got
a 20-second standing ovation before his first at-bat. Larkin backed
out of the box, waved to the fans, then lowered his head and stood
motionless while the cheers washed over him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had to step out. I was very appreciative,'' Larkin said.
''It's an emotional time for me. I think you could see it in the
mistakes I made out there today.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin went 1-for-5, struck out twice, hit into a double play
and grounded into a forceout with the bases loaded, lowering his
average to .322.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets considered flying a contingent of team officials,
manager Bobby Valentine and players Lenny Harris and John Franco to
Cincinnati following their game Saturday afternoon in Atlanta, but
couldn't get arrangements worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wanted to get an audience with Barry and see if we could
convince him this is the place to play,'' Phillips said. ''We hope
he wants to come, make a run at the playoffs, make a run at the
World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin will be a free agent after this season, when he makes
$5.3 million. He was coming off a National League MVP season when
he agreed to an extension in 1996 that was well below market value,
but wants a better contract this time.
</P>
<P>
   If Larkin ends up leaving, he'll be the second player claimed by
the club's midseason slump, joining Denny Neagle, who was traded to
the Yankees for prospects a day after the All-Star game.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he doesn't come, I'll understand,'' said Franco, who spoke
to Larkin by phone. ''It's a tough situation for him and his
family. He's been there his whole career. We'll sit back and wait
for his decision. Hopefully, it will be the right decision for
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
