<HEADLINE> Probe Continues in Torricelli Funds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Federal prosecutors have begun questioning
aides to Sen. Robert Torricelli after obtaining guilty pleas from
people who made illegal contributions to his 1996 Senate campaign,
according to published reports.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Stern, an executive assistant to Torricelli, took the
Fifth Amendment when she was subpoenaed to testify on June 2 in
Newark before a grand jury investigating political donor David
Chang, according to Saturday's editions of The New York Times. amd
The Record of Hackensack and
</P>
<P>
   People close to the senator told The New York Times that several
other aides have also been questioned by prosecutors and the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week with the Times, Torricelli said he
believed the federal investigation into his campaign fund raising
had ended when Chang, who lives in Cresskill, pleaded guilty to
campaign finance violations.
</P>
<P>
   But attorneys familiar with the case told both newspapers that
the investigation has been continuing since Chang decided to
cooperate with authorities in exchange for a lighter sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Chang is among 25 people charged by the Campaign Financing Task
Force and among seven who have admitted wrongdoing in connection
with Torricelli fund-raising efforts. None of the seven has
implicated the New Jersey Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli isn't accused of any wrongdoing. He has maintained he
was unaware of the improper donations and has said all such money
is donated to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli raised $9.2 million to defeat Rep. Richard A. Zimmer
in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
