<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans nominate Waterbury mayor for U.S. Senate  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRFIELD, Conn. (AP) - Waterbury Mayor Philip Giordano,
acknowledging he has a tough race to run, accepted the Republican
nomination for the U.S. Senate Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano spent much of his acceptance speech at the state
Republican convention attacking the record of his opponent,
two-term U.S. Sen. Joseph Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed Lieberman for Connecticut's high federal tax burden
and for the loss of defense jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Other senators around the country are doing justice to their
states, but our senator, Joe Lieberman, is not doing justice to our
state,'' Giordano said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman spokesman Dan Gerstein defended the senator's record.
He said even Republican leaders - including state party Chairman
Chris DePino - have called Lieberman the ''conscious of the
Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman plans to run a vigorous campaign, Gerstein added, and
will continue let people know what he has done for the state.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-year-old Waterbury mayor said, if elected, he would
support Republican tax plans, like the elimination of the marriage
penalty and the estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano also pledged to support a Constitutional amendment
against burning the American flag, and he said he would vote to ban
the late-term abortion procedure known as ''partial-birth
abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Giordano admitted it would be a difficult campaign against
Lieberman, who enjoyed a 5-to-1 vote of support in a Quinnipiac
University poll this week.
</P>
<P>
   He likened his campaign to U.S. forces during the Battle of the
Bulge, who refused to surrender and eventually defeated Germany.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 of the state's 1,400 delegates came to the
convention at Sacred Heart University to support Giordano and to
vote for the party's eight members of the electoral college.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters waved purple and white Giordano signs and paraded to
rock music by Kiss and Van Halen as Giordano took the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano began his speech with welcomes in English, Italian and
Spanish, reflecting his Italian ethnicity and his childhood in
Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   ''And who says the Republican party is not the party of
inclusion?'' he asked the crowd, who answered with applause.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano came to Waterbury when he was 5 years old, graduated
from parochial schools and served in the U.S. Marine Corps.
</P>
<P>
   After his military service, he earned a law degree and became an
assistant in the city's legal office.
</P>
<P>
   His political career began in 1995 with election to the state
House of Representatives. Later that year, he was elected mayor,
and he has been re-elected twice since.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano cited his accomplishments as mayor: no tax increase in
three years, a drop in crime he attributed to community policing
and innovative public school ideas, such as mandatory uniforms and
summer school.
</P>
<P>
   His leadership in Waterbury has not been without controversy,
however.
</P>
<P>
   The Commission on Human Rights and Opportunities investigated
hiring practices in the public schools after the Waterbury
Republican-American reported widespread patronage within the school
department.
</P>
<P>
   Reports also said affirmative action policies were ignored,
leaving Waterbury schools with the lowest ratio of minority
teachers out of the state's five largest school districts.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference after the convention, Giordano attributed
the CHRO investigation to the complaint of a ''local radical.'' He
said the investigation has been going on for 1&AMP;frac12; years, without
action from the agency.
</P>
<P>
   The city also has had well-publicized financial troubles brought
on by the bankruptcy of a firm hired to collect its taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano laid off 170 city employees earlier this year after the
city's 11 unions rejected his request to take four furlough days
before the end of the fiscal year. Giordano said he had no choice
but to lay off workers or raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The unions eventually agreed to concessions and most of the
laid-off workers got their jobs back.
</P>
</TEXT>
