<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman To Lead Moderate Baptists  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) -- The Cooperative Baptist Fellowship,
formed 10 years ago as a moderate alternative to the Southern
Baptist Convention, has appointed another woman to its top
leadership position.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Forrester is the first ordained woman and fifth woman
named to lead the 1,800-church fellowship. She has been the
minister of pastoral care and counseling at Greenville First
Baptist Church since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester, 50, was elected moderator at the Cooperative Baptist
Fellowship's convention in Orlando earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   The Cooperative Baptist Fellowship sends out its own
missionaries and supports moderate seminaries. Churches can be
members of the fellowship and the 41,000-church Southern Baptist
Convention at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Greenville First Baptist was an early contributor of the
fellowship, and Forrester was an early moderator on the state
level.
</P>
<P>
   ''She has drive and energy and initiative, but she would not
have sought this position,'' said Fred Andrea, moderator of the
state fellowship. ''This position sought her.''
</P>
<P>
   Forrester was first woman on her church's pastoral staff. She
paid her way through seminary while working as a full-time
psychiatric nurse. As she completed her doctorate, she practiced in
an alcohol and drug treatment center.
</P>
<P>
   As a preacher's daughter growing up in Columbia, the church she
attended had no female deacons. But ''from a very early age, I was
taught by women and was told, 'You listen to God and be whatever
God wants you to be,''' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
