<HEADLINE> Spain Socialist Party Picks Leader  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM BROWN
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- Spain's Socialist Party on Saturday chose
as its new leader a 39-year-old lawmaker who promised to rejuvenate
the party and end internal squabbling that has hurt it at the
polls.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Luis Rodriguez Zapatero, a congressman from the northern
Leon region who has been with the party since he was 19, must now
form a leadership group, which will face a vote of approval from
the party congress on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez Zapatero now faces the task of bolstering the
fragmented Socialist Party -- an all the more difficult job since
the overwhelming March 12 election victory of center-right Prime
Minister Jose Maria Aznar and his Popular Party.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's vote, Rodriguez Zapatero defeated his three
opponents by a narrow margin, dealing a surprise upset to Jose
Bono, a 49-year-old criminal lawyer who was the favorite after 17
years as the president of the Castilla-La Mancha regional
government.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before the vote, Rodriguez Zapatero, who benefited from
the vote of younger party members, pleaded for party unity and said
he would seek to restore the party by a return to its ideals. He
promised to reach out to small businessmen and the self-employed
and work to increase the number of women in Spain's work force.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Felipe Gonzalez, the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party
ruled for nearly 14 years starting in 1982, and for many Spaniards,
it is synonymous with their country's successful transition to
democracy after decades of dictatorship under Gen. Francisco
Franco, who died in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   But the party was voted out of office in 1996, in large part due
to corruption scandals. Its popularity continued to crumble as the
party leadership appeared more interested in political infighting
than revamping the party's image or coming up with new policies.
</P>
<P>
   The defeats at the polls drove Socialist leader and candidate
Joaquin Almunia to resign, paving the way for this vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
