<HEADLINE> Catholics Called To Pay Slave Labor  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Lawmakers from across the political spectrum are
calling on the Roman Catholic Church to pay into a fund to
compensate Nazi-era slave and forced laborers.
</P>
<P>
   Otto Lambsdorff, the German government's chief envoy on the Nazi
labor issue, said the church shares in the universal responsibility
that Germany has for Nazi labor policies.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the last years of the war, one couldn't have run an
organization without forced laborers because all the other people
able to the do the work were in the Wehrmacht,'' said Lambsdorff in
an interview with Bild am Sonntag newspaper to be published Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Media reports in the last week have said that the Catholic
Church used forced laborers.
</P>
<P>
   A church in Bavaria used 16 Russian and four Polish forced
laborers, along with 19 French prisoners of war, according to the
German Bishops Conference. Records show the laborers were paid for
their work.
</P>
<P>
   Church officials in Berlin are also investigating whether forced
laborers worked in cemeteries. The officials told the Berliner
Morgenpost newspaper they would not make a decision on paying into
the fund until they made a determination, which they expect by the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's Catholic church has said it had no plans to make a
general contribution to the fund, though it has not ruled out
contributions by local churches.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives involved in talks on resolving one of the last
unaddressed evils of the Nazi regime signed a historic agreement
this week on a $5 billion fund to compensate surviving laborers.
</P>
<P>
   The fund includes money for slave laborers -- intended to
literally be worked to death in concentration camps -- and also
forced laborers deported from their homes in eastern Europe to keep
the German war machine running.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3,000 German businesses have pledged $1.5 billion so
far to the $5 billion fund, which is to be financed 50-50 by
industry and the government.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawmakers calling on the church to pay include Max
Stadler, a Free Democrat parliament member, who pointed out that
the Evangelical Church has already pledged to contribute $5 million
to the fund.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would wish for such a gesture independent of whether the
church participated in the forced labor system,'' the head of
parliament's internal affairs committee, Ute Vogt, a Social
Democrat, told the Welt am Sonntag newspaper in an interview to be
published Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1 million former laborers are expected to be eligible
for payments, which Germany hopes to begin this year.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.stiftungsinitiative.de/eindex.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-22-00 1903 </TRAILER>
