<HEADLINE> Moulds Charged Up for Bills Season  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN WAWROW
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSFORD, N.Y. (AP) -- It hasn't taken Eric Moulds long to find
his graceful stride and soft hands.
</P>
<P>
   Picking up from where he left off last year, Moulds is already
making remarkable catches, electrifying the crowd and making
defenders shake their heads in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo Bills receiver is feeling so well that he was
considering pulling back the reins Saturday. Heck, it's only two
days into training camp, and he is looking ahead to a big season.
</P>
<P>
   Why waste it now?
</P>
<P>
   ''(Defensive coordinator) Ted Cottrell came up to me at lunch
and told me that he was going to start doubling me if I keep doing
those types of things,'' Moulds said. ''So I had better slow down a
little bit because I want to try to get some one-on-one coverage,
and get some work.''
</P>
<P>
   Moulds will get plenty of work this year. With Andre Reed's
departure, Moulds officially attains the status as the Bills' go-to
wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Unofficially, Moulds has been the man since his breakout season
in 1998 when he broke Reed's franchise record and led the AFC with
1,368 yards in receptions. Despite a nagging hamstring injury last
season, Moulds still led the Bills with 994 yards and seven
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Fully recovered, Moulds said he feels ''more explosive.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think I can do a lot better than that,'' he said, referring
to his 1998 numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Helping motivate Moulds is this being the final year of his
contract. He can't help but consider the multimillion-dollar prize
that could be awaiting him next winter.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're a competitor, and you see all these guys getting these
big contracts and, of course, you would like to be in that
situation,'' Moulds said. ''But you still have to go out this year
and have a good showing.''
</P>
<P>
   Having kept track of the team's offseason moves to clear room
under the salary cap, Moulds hoped some of that was being saved for
him because he wants to remain a Bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to be here and I'm pretty sure it'll get done,'' he
said. ''But I just go out there and approach it that if I play well
then I figure they'll take care of it.''
</P>
<P>
   How well Moulds does depends on how well Peerless Price handles
the responsibility of taking over the No. 2 wide receiver job.
Coming off a promising rookie season, Price will have to prove
himself a consistent threat in order to take the pressure off of
Moulds.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what I'm looking for,'' Price said. ''I know he's the
go-to guy. He's pushing me and telling me to take some of the
pressure off of him. That's what I'm looking to do and, in the
process, have a great season myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Price finished with 359 yards and three touchdowns, while
starting in four games last season. This winter, he hired a
personal trainer to make sure he was prepared for this year.
</P>
<P>
   Price has looked strong in camp, but it is Moulds who has been
most impressive.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can see Eric Moulds is ready to play,'' coach Wade Phillips
said. ''The defensive coaches just shake their heads when it's him
making the play, because the defensive back was in good position
and (Moulds) still made the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Antoine Winfield had a running battle with Moulds
during Saturday morning's session.
</P>
<P>
   ''Competing against Eric Moulds, a Pro Bowler, only can get
myself better,'' Winfield said. ''He was good. He's in great shape.
... I think he's one of the top receivers in the league right
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
