<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Missing since 1944, remains of New York airman returned  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Pvt. Vincent J. Netherwood has finally come
home, his body returned to his family after laying hidden atop a
Chinese mountain for nearly six decades.
</P>
<P>
   Netherwood was 20 in 1944. He was engaged to be married after
World War II ended.
</P>
<P>
   For him and nine other U.S. airmen, the war ended in 1944 when
their plane crashed into a mountainside in China. For 56 years, his
family - including six brothers and sisters - wondered if they
would ever be able to bury their kin in his hometown of Kingston.
</P>
<P>
   The remains were found in a rugged ravine on Mao'er Mountain in
Guangxi province. All 10 airmen died when their B-24 bomber crashed
during a return flight to Guangxi after bombing Japanese ships near
Taiwan on Aug. 31, 1944.
</P>
<P>
   According to U.S. military records, the crew members in addition
to tail gunner Netherwood were pilot 2nd Lt. George H. Pierpont;
co-pilot 2nd Lt. Franklin A. Tomenendale; navigator 2nd Lt. Robert
L. Deming; bombardier 2nd Lt. George A. Ward; engineer Staff Sgt.
Anthony W. DeLucia; radio operator Sgt. Ellsworth V. Kelley; radar
observer Pfc. Fred P. Buckley; and gunners Staff Sgt. William A.
Drager, Sgt. Robert L. Kearsey.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Defense did not provide the men's hometowns.
They were members of the 375th Bomber Squadron.
</P>
<P>
   The bomber crash site lay undisturbed for 52 years until two
Chinese farmers hunting for wild herbs found it on Oct. 2, 1996.
The discovery was made public in November 1996 when Chinese
President Jiang Zemin turned over photographs of five dog tags
taken from the aircraft, as well as a videotape of the crash site,
to President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The United States poured aid and bomber crews into China during
World War II to fight the Japanese, who had invaded much of the
country. About 1,000 U.S. planes went down over China during the
war, and about 100 remain missing.
</P>
<P>
   Netherwood's body was returned to his family on Saturday,
arriving at Albany International Airport into the waiting hands of
family members who took the body home to be buried next to his
parents. The New York State Police escorted the body down the
Thruway and the Kingston police picked up the escort at the city
line.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our family never gave up hope,'' said John Leirey, one of
Netherwood's nephews. ''When they found the plane, they found my
uncle's dog tags which told us that that was his final resting
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Leirey said the dog tags and a ring were returned to the family.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really been a blessing for us,'' Leirey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-22-00 1917 </TRAILER>
