<HEADLINE> Giants 5, Dodgers 2  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Livan Hernandez pitched eight strong innings
in his 100th career start and the San Francisco Giants got home
runs from Rich Aurilia, Bobby Estalella and Armando Rios as they
beat the Los Angeles Dodgers 5-2 Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez (9-7) retired 13 consecutive batters during one
stretch before giving up a leadoff single in the eighth to Adrian
Beltre and a one-out homer to Kevin Elster.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez allowed five hits, struck out six and walked one. The
MVP of the 1997 NLCS and World Series with the Florida Marlins is
9-3 in his last 15 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Robb Nen worked the ninth for his 22nd save. The Giants won for
the 15th time in 19 games.
</P>
<P>
   Aurilia, Estalella and Rios homered to give San Francisco a 5-0
lead after four innings against rookie Eric Gagne (1-6).
</P>
<P>
   Aurilia hit his 10th homer with two outs in the second. Rios
followed with a double and scored on Estalella's 10th homer.
</P>
<P>
   Rios connected in the fourth after a two-out walk to Aurilia.
</P>
<P>
   Estalella, who has hit four of his home runs this year in games
Hernandez has pitched, also threw out two potential base stealers.
He nailed Todd Hollandsworth at second base after a second-inning
walk, and later completed a strikeout-double play by getting Shawn
Green at third.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Neither Gary Sheffield nor Barry Bonds homered in their
head-to-head duel for the major league lead. Sheffield, whose
fourth-inning bid was caught on the warning track, still leads
Bonds 33-32. Bonds went 0-for-4 and struck out twice. ... J.T.
Snow's next two RBIs will increase his career total to 600. He is
one of only five switch-hitters to drive in 100 runs in a season in
both the NL and AL, along with Ted Simmons, Ken Singleton, Eddie
Murray and Bobby Bonilla. ... Hernandez, who singled in the fifth,
has hit safely in 22 of his last 35 starts and is 25-for-89 during
that span.
</P>
