<HEADLINE> Iran Lawyers Freed on Bail  </HEADLINE>
By ALI AKBAR DAREINI
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Officials released on bail Saturday two
pro-reform lawyers jailed in connection with a videotape that
alleged links between hard-line politicians and Islamic vigilante
attacks, according to a relative.
</P>
<P>
   Mohsen Rahami, a university professor and cleric, and Shirin
Ebadi, a pro-democracy and women's rights activist, were arrested
late last month because of allegations against some officials made
in the tape recording.
</P>
<P>
   Ebadi's husband, Javad Tavassolian, told The Associated Press
that the two had been released on $3,300 bail Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   He said his wife had denied the charges against her, and that
she and Rahami were to appear Sunday at the third hearing of their
closed-door trial. Tavassolian refused to give any other details.
</P>
<P>
   The widely circulated videotape featured Amir Farshad Ebrahimi,
a member of an Islamic vigilante group, who identifies several
senior hard-liners in the government who he claims used his group
to attack reformist opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Vigilantes frequently have struck reformist meetings and
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Ebrahimi, according to the state-run media, has recanted his
confessions, claiming the lawyers pressured him to make the
statements.
</P>
<P>
   Five more people, all believed to be reformists, were arrested
earlier this month on the same allegations. There were no reports
on whether they had been freed.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over the videotape comes amid a power struggle
between reformists, led by President Mohammad Khatami, and
hard-liners, who dominate many parts of the government and look for
support to Iran's supreme leader, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
   The judiciary has become the hard-liners' most powerful tool. In
the past two months, the judiciary has closed many reformist
newspapers and ordered the detention of several pro-democracy
journalists and activists. Courts have overlooked violence
committed by hard-line vigilantes against reformists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
