<HEADLINE> Ramseys, Boulder Cops To Meet  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- John and Patsy Ramsey have agreed on a
date next month to meet with Boulder police about the 1996 slaying
of their daughter JonBenet.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side would reveal the date. Boulder Police Chief Mark
Beckner would say only that the meeting will be after Aug. 18
because of scheduling conflicts with his officers.
</P>
<P>
   Lin Wood, the Ramseys' Atlanta attorney, said the meeting will
occur before the end of August, ''but I will not disclose specific
days because I don't want to see my office turned into a campground
for the media.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple were to meet with police this weekend in Atlanta,
where the Ramseys now live, but had to reschedule because of
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting would be the first between the Ramseys and police
since June 1998. Earlier meeting proposals fell through because of
differing conditions from each side.
</P>
<P>
   Six-year-old JonBenet was found dead in the family's Boulder
home Dec. 26, 1996. No one has been arrested, but Boulder police
have said the Ramseys remain under suspicion. The Ramseys have
denied any involvement.
</P>
</TEXT>
