<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> King Plays On Despite Strained Back  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY ARMOUR
<TEXT>
<P>
   GURNEE, Ill. (AP) -- Betsy King walked up the 18th fairway in
tears, the pain in her back almost too much to bear.
</P>
<P>
   ''By the time I got to the third tee, I could barely swing,''
King said. ''I didn't make one shot out there without pain.''
</P>
<P>
   King, 44, a two-time U.S. Women's Open winner and honorary Merit
Club member, began the day in good shape, tied with Karrie Webb at
3 under and just one stroke behind leader Meg Mallon. But as she
teed off on the second hole, she felt something pop.
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious even before she called for an LPGA Tour trainer
on the third hole that she was in pain. She kneaded her lower back
to try and loosen up the muscle, and tried to stretch it out as she
stood over her ball.
</P>
<P>
   But when she went to put her tee into the ground on the fourth
hole, she couldn't even bend over and had to crouch down.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it was any other tournament or if I was in another
position, I don't know if I would have continued,'' said King, who
was diagnosed later with a strained back.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief conversation with U.S. Golf Association officials,
she was allowed to get treatment between the fifth and six holes. A
trainer massaged her back, applied some therapeutic balm and gave
her some Advil.
</P>
<P>
   The pain wouldn't go away, though, and it affected her game.
Starting with the fifth hole, she had six straight bogeys. She
finally made par on the par-3 No. 11, then followed it with another
two bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   She finished with a 10-over 82, dropping her 14 strokes back and
out of contention.
</P>
<P>
   As she walked up the 18th fairway, King fought back tears.
Mallon, her playing partner, patted her on the back and gave her a
hug.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was sick for Betsy,'' Mallon said. ''It was one of the
bravest rounds I've ever seen anybody play. ... She said it felt
like it was a knife coming through her back every time she swung. I
felt terrible for her.''
</P>
<P>
   King went for more treatment after her round and hopes to play
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   NO CONSOLATION PRIZE: Forget that Laura Davies is among the
statistical leaders in the U.S. Women's Open. It's the leaderboard
that counts.
</P>
<P>
   Davies ranks second in greens in regulation, making 80 percent
of them. She's tied for fourth in fairways hit at 81 percent. But
she's seven shots back from Karrie Webb at even-par 216.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel like I could be seven, eight or nine under the way I
played,'' said Davies, who shot a 72 Saturday. ''I'm not there and
(Webb) is, so she must be playing well.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to play better yourself,'' Davies added. ''You can't
expect Karrie to struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   TAKING THE SHORTCUT: Meg Mallon ran into a few potholes on her
detour.
</P>
<P>
   With the wind blowing and the pin on the par-4 14th on the back,
left side, Mallon again took her shortcut through the 13th fairway
Saturday. But her tee shot landed too far left, putting her behind
the big oak tree on the alleyway to the green.
</P>
<P>
   She chipped onto the green, landing about 25 feet past the pin,
and then two-putted for bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was the smartest play for me, the way the wind was blowing
and where the pin was,'' Mallon said. ''The only thing was, I just
hit it a little too far left. So I had to hit one shorter club, but
I had plenty to get it over the tree and make it over the green. I
don't think I got a very good break by the way it bounced.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EAGLE EYE: Sophie Gustafson was the only player with an eagle
Saturday. The Swede eagled the par-5 18th hole.
</P>
</TEXT>
