<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Janikowski Arrives at Raiders Camp  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPA, Calif. (AP) -- Kicker Sebastian Janikowski was unwilling to
talk about his brushes with the law or the terms of his
multimillion dollar contract Saturday as the Oakland Raiders opened
training camp with their first-round draft pick in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Janikowski signed a five-year contract worth $6.05
million, including a $2 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived about 1:30 a.m. Saturday, and was on the field for
the team's first practice later in the morning. He made five of
seven attempts, although his first try caromed off the uprights.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida State star was subdued as he spoke after practice,
and wouldn't discuss his recent arrest in Florida for possession of
the so-called ''date-rape'' drug.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to talk about that,'' Janikowski said. ''People
make mistakes off the field. I will try to do better. I know there
will be pressure on me, but I like being under pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Janikowski's contract also includes a clause that will force him
to pay back about $25,000 for every game he misses due to
suspension. The clause was added because of the kicker's run-ins
with the law.
</P>
<P>
   Janikowski is free on bond and awaiting arraignment in
Tallahassee on charges of possession of the drug GHB. Until the
arraignment, he is allowed to travel out of state for work.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the issue is that Janikowski is a citizen of Poland,
and could face deportation if he has further scrapes with the law.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Janikowski was acquitted of trying to bribe a
Florida police officer.
</P>
<P>
   His contract also includes a clause that guarantees his salary
for three seasons if he scores 114 or more points this season and
stays out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a pretty good deal,'' he said, refusing to elaborate.
''It's between my agent and my team.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Bryant, a second-year defensive end for the Raiders, who
also came out of Florida State, said he's been talking to
Janikowski regularly since he was drafted.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is a young guy who just got caught up with the wrong crowd
by going back there (to Florida after the June minicamp),'' Bryant
said. ''He has to leave this behind him and grow up and realize
this is his job now. He can't risk throwing it away.''
</P>
<P>
   Raiders coach Jon Gruden reiterated the Raiders will stand
behind Janikowski.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm confident the young man will learn from this and that
everything will be resolved. ... I'd like to let him move on,''
Gruden said.
</P>
<P>
   Janikowski made 66 of 83 field goals in three years at Florida
State and became the third-leading scorer in Seminoles history.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders could use him. They finished last in the AFC in
field-goal percentage last season. Janikowski was the first kicker
selected in the first round since 1979.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
