<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, July 22, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Danforth Emerges in Bush Veepstakes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush said he would decide on a running mate by
tomorrow, as former Missouri Sen. John Danforth emerged today as another
potential candidate. Bush must decide between former Defense Secretary Dick
Cheney, described as the leading candidate, and a secret list of other potential
running mates. Danforth, his wife Sally, and Cheney -- who also heads Bush's
search team -- met secretly with Bush in a Chicago hotel suite Tuesday. He is
said to be under consideration, though two highly placed Republican officials
said yesterday that Cheney was the leading candidate.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Kenya Suffers Massive Power Cut
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- Power went off across Kenya on Saturday and the nation
of 29 million people will be largely without electricity for the next two days
because of technical problems, the electric company said. Electricity went off
about 6:30 p.m. throughout the capital, Nairobi, and in most other parts of the
country. In a statement on national radio, the Kenya Power and Lighting Company
said a ''major fault'' had occurred in transmission of power from neighboring
Uganda. It said the problem would take two days to fix.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Denounces GOP Tax Breaks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton contended today that tax cuts sought by
the Republican-led Congress over the past two years are so enormous they would
''completely erase'' the projected budget surplus and disproportionately benefit
the wealthy. In the GOP's response, Sen. Rod Grams laid out a case for Clinton
to reconsider his threat to veto recent bills intended to ease the income tax
marriage penalty and repeal inheritance taxes. Clinton cited a White House
analysis released today that estimates the 10-year cost of major tax cuts passed
or moving in the Republican-led Congress at $712 billion.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fla. Murder Suspect Holds Hostages
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- A man suspected of killing a store clerk was holding up
to six people hostage in a house Saturday, including two juveniles, authorities
said. The suspect, Jamie Petron, reportedly shot the homeowner's son, who was
released around 2:30 p.m. and taken to a hospital with injuries that weren't
believed to be life-threatening. Petron, 41, fled to the house after ramming a
deputy sheriff's vehicle and shooting the deputy in the leg, authorities said.
Orange County Sheriff's Department SWAT officials surrounded the house where
Petron fled.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mideast Peace Talks in Low Gear
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- The Middle East summit is in low gear in deference to
the Jewish Sabbath, but negotiations are going on, quietly and informally, as
Israeli and Palestinian leaders await President Clinton's return. Traditional
Jews devote Saturday to prayer and rest; secular Israelis normally do neither.
But it could be politically unwise for an Israeli official to conduct normal
business on that day. Clinton, attending an economic summit in Japan, trimmed
his schedule so he could return to the Camp David talks by Sunday evening.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
18 in N.C. Accused of Hezbollah Aid
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Federal authorities arrested 18 suspects in raids of
houses and businesses, saying at least some of them were members of a
cigarette-smuggling ring that was raising money for the Islamic militant group
Hezbollah. Seventeen of the suspects were arrested in and around Charlotte, and
one person was nabbed in Michigan. All were indicted on federal charges
including immigration violations, weapons offenses, money laundering and
cigarette trafficking, U.S. Attorney Mark Calloway said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
New Moon Found Orbiting Jupiter
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Astronomers at the University of Arizona and their
Massachusetts colleagues say they have found a 17th moon orbiting Jupiter. If
confirmed, the 3-mile-diameter moon would be the smallest known satellite of a
major planet and the first Jovian moon discovered in 21 years. ''When you
realize that you were the first person to lay eyes on something that had not
been seen before, that's kind of a good feeling,'' University of Arizona
astronomer Jeff Larsen.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Woods Extends British Open Lead
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland (AP) -- Tiger Woods extended his lead at the British
Open despite two rare bogeys today and moved closer to becoming the youngest
player ever to win the career Grand Slam. Woods shot a 67 in the third round to
open up a six-stroke lead over David Duval and Thomas Bjorn. Woods shook off the
bogeys to pick up three more strokes on his closest pursuers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Athletics Crush Angels 10-3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Ben Grieve hit a grand slam and Barry Zito won his
major league debut, escaping a fifth-inning jam in impressive fashion, as the
Oakland Athletics defeated the Anaheim Angels 10-3 today. Grieve's slam was his
second of the season and the ninth for the A's this year, a franchise record.
Zito (1-0) allowed one run on two hits in five innings.
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA 
