<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Tabloid Names Pedophiles  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP ) -- A British tabloid on Sunday began publishing the
photos and identifications of thousands of people it says are child
sex offenders, and announced a Web site that can be used to
determine if a pedophile lives nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The weekly News of the World published 49 photos on a single
page and carried identifying details and locations -- if available --
but not addresses. But it did not say where it acquired either the
information or the photographs.
</P>
<P>
   The tabloid dedicated its campaign against pedophiles to
8-year-old Sarah Payne, who disappeared July 1 in West Sussex,
southern England, and whose naked body was found two weeks later in
a field 15 miles from where she had disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site also includes the names and photos and features a
map of England on which readers can click on their region to see a
list of people the newspaper says are pedophiles living there.
</P>
<P>
   The News of the World said there were 110,000 proven pedophiles
in the United Kingdom and that it would not stop its campaign until
they had all been named.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said the move was aimed at alerting and warning
the public about those named and was ''absolutely not a charter for
vigilantes.''
</P>
<P>
   But the chief executive of the children's charity Childline said
the newspaper's actions held risks.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is concerning when laws and provisions put in place to deal
with this situation are by-passed or risk people taking the law
into their own hands,'' said Valerie Howarth. ''You risk innocent
members of the public being wrongly identified and targeted, and
you risk driving pedophiles to move from place to place, possibly
becoming more dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper denied that its action would encourage vigilantes.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial, the newspaper said, ''We do NOT want any
vigilante action or violence against these people. Knowledge is the
only weapon the community needs. We do NOT want our readers to take
any action. We do NOT want them to break the law.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.newsoftheworld.co.uk/forsarah/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
