<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syracuse police say artist's mural carries gang label  </HEADLINE>
By Luis Perez
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - The first police officer who pulled up to
the Sunshine Market wanted to know what Oliver Fox was doing.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-year-old artist explained that the store manager had
hired him to spray paint a mural on his building after seeing his
work for Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Then a state police cruiser stopped at the market at Delaware
and Grace streets in Syracuse. The trooper went through the same
routine.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 minutes later, four police cars stopped, including Sgt.
Dave Pauldine, who represents the Syracuse Police Department on the
Syracuse &AMP; Onondaga County Graffiti Busters Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's offense: His tag - ESAN - the stylized graffiti signature
he likes to use, is gang related, according to police.
</P>
<P>
   Fox was not only forced to paint over his tag, but he lost his
most lucrative client, Coca-Cola, after city officials complained
about his work. Coca-Cola sponsors a nationwide ''Art in Harmony''
program that pays artists to paint promotional murals for Coke.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Brockman, Coca-Cola's Art of Harmony coordinator, said she
received a phone call from Mayor Roy Bernardi's office this week
about Fox. The phone call was enough for her not to work with him
again and the first criticism she's heard of the program.
</P>
<P>
   Fox found out Friday that Coca-Cola wouldn't work with him
again. ''I'm upset,'' he said. ''I don't think City Hall has any
right to do that. I think this is harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who plans to attend the School of Visual Arts in Manhattan,
caused a stir last year when the Graffiti Busters Coalition
targeted some of his work. Even though local business owners paid
Fox to spray paint elaborate murals, some think his work is a
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Horace Jones Jr., who owns Markee Cuts, was forced
to defend one of Fox's mural on the side of his business. In the
end, officials let the mural of Chuckie, a horror movie character,
stay.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola commissioned Fox to paint murals on two Sunshine
Market walls, paying him $1,400 for the job. One mural, in shades
of blue, purple and red, is of Eskimos holding Coca-Cola bottles
under a star-filled night with a half moon. The other is a night
scene of a lighthouse with a red beam of light flashing over the
water. The Coke logo appears at the center of the beam.
</P>
<P>
   Store manager Ray Aziz liked the job and asked Fox to do the
whole wall to help clean up the neighborhood. Fox chose to spray
paint scenes from Aesop's Fables combined with a fantasy theme. The
characters Fox painted include a giant monkey dressed in a king's
robe; an owl, glasses perched low on its nose as it watches a mouse
gnawing at its tree; and a fairy playing the flute.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the offending tag of ''ESAN.'' Police say the
tag, chosen because Fox likes the way the letters go together,
represent a street gang in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. David Sackett, a Syracuse police spokesman, had no comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-22-00 2021 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
