<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, July 22, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Danforth Emerges as Bush VP Candidate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former Sen. John Danforth resurfaced tonight as a
Republican vice presidential candidate, joining former Defense Secretary Dick
Cheney on George W. Bush's short list. Cheney is the leading candidate, a highly
placed Republican official said as the Texas governor neared his decision.
Danforth, his wife Sally, and Cheney -- who also heads Bush's search team -- met
secretly with Bush in a Chicago hotel suite Tuesday, setting aside his
oft-stated opposition to serving as vice president. Bush said he will make his
decision this weekend and announce it this week.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cubans To Protest U.S. Trade Embargo
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Cuba will begin national celebrations to mark the start of the
revolution that brought Fidel Castro to power 41 years ago with a large
demonstration in Havana to protest the U.S. trade embargo, an official newspaper
said today. The Communist Party daily Granma said that participants will march
down the Malecon coastal highway on Wednesday morning to the U.S. Interests
Section to ''express to the world their profound and indignant rejection against
the monstrous genocidal policy applied against our people.'' It called the
embargo, imposed shortly after Castro's rise to power, ''the most prolonged
blockade that has existed in history.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Kenya Suffers Massive Power Cut
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- Power went off across Kenya on Saturday and the nation
of 29 million people will be largely without electricity for the next two days
because of technical problems, the electric company said. Electricity went off
about 6:30 p.m. throughout the capital, Nairobi, and in most other parts of the
country. In a statement on national radio, the Kenya Power and Lighting Company
said a ''major fault'' had occurred in transmission of power from neighboring
Uganda. It said the problem would take two days to fix.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Denounces GOP Tax Breaks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton contended today that tax cuts sought by
the Republican-led Congress over the past two years are so enormous they would
''completely erase'' the projected budget surplus and disproportionately benefit
the wealthy. In the GOP's response, Sen. Rod Grams laid out a case for Clinton
to reconsider his threat to veto recent bills intended to ease the income tax
marriage penalty and repeal inheritance taxes. Clinton cited a White House
analysis released today that estimates the 10-year cost of major tax cuts passed
or moving in the Republican-led Congress at $712 billion.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fla. Murder Suspect Holds Hostages
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- An armed man who allegedly killed a store clerk was
holding five people hostage in a home today in a standoff with sheriff's
deputies, authorities said. Jamie Dean Petron, 41, shot a Broward County
sheriff's deputy in the leg in a grocery store parking lot before fleeing to the
nearby home. The hostages being held were one adult, a teen-ager and three young
children, said Orange County Sheriff's Sgt. Bernie Presha. Petron shot a
28-year-old man in the home, authorities said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
New Moon Found Orbiting Jupiter
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Astronomers at the University of Arizona and their
Massachusetts colleagues say they have found a 17th moon orbiting Jupiter. If
confirmed, the 3-mile-diameter moon would be the smallest known satellite of a
major planet and the first Jovian moon discovered in 21 years. ''When you
realize that you were the first person to lay eyes on something that had not
been seen before, that's kind of a good feeling,'' University of Arizona
astronomer Jeff Larsen.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Thousands Apply for 'The Sopranos'
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HARRISON, N.J. (AP) -- Thousands of Soprano wannabes turned out at a casting
call at Harrison High School today, some dreaming of becoming the next Salvatore
''Big Pussy'' Bompensiero, the snitch who got whacked last season and ended up
in a watery grave. Lines stretched for blocks and people left out were told to
mail their applications.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Woods Extends British Open Lead
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland (AP) -- Tiger Woods proved he was human Saturday,
making his first bogey in 64 holes of major championship golf, but still managed
to double his lead at the British Open. Woods shot a 67 in the third round to
open up a six-stroke lead over David Duval and Thomas Bjorn. Unless the
24-year-old Woods suffers the greatest collapse in the history of golf's oldest
championship, he will become the youngest player to win the Grand Slam.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Devil Rays Crush Yankees 12-4
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- David Cone lost his career-high seventh straight decision
despite making his strongest start in a month, allowing a home run to Greg
Vaughn as Tampa Bay snapped a four-game skid with a 12-4 win over the New York
Yankees today. The right-hander (1-9) allowed three runs and six hits in six
innings.
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA 
</P>
