<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Could Lose Billions in Revenue  </HEADLINE>
By LEON BARKHO
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- Iraq stands to lose more than $1.5 billion
in oil revenues this year as Saudi Arabia raises production to try
to bring down world fuel prices, Iraq's oil minister said in
remarks published Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Saudi decision to pump more oil has ''caused huge financial
losses for the Iraqi people, which may exceed $1.5 billion this
year,'' Oil Minister Amer Mohammed Rashid was quoted as saying in
the government newspaper al-Jumhouriya.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia, the world's largest oil exporter, announced
earlier this month that it will try to drive down prices by as much
as $5 per barrel from then-current levels of $30 per barrel by
adding 500,000 barrels a day to its output.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia's announcement drew harsh criticism from Iraq,
which accuses the Saudis of neglecting the interests of their own
people and of other partners in the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting countries to appease Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Other OPEC members also criticized the unilateral decision,
saying it was made under pressure from the United States, which is
seeking relief for consumers as gas prices surge above $2 per
gallon in some parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq, which is under U.N. sanctions for its 1990 invasion of
Kuwait that led to the Gulf War, is allowed unlimited oil sales
under a United Nations-approved program. Proceeds, however, go to a
U.N. fund to be used only to buy food, medicine and other essential
goods. Some of the revenues may also go to modernize Iraq's oil
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Rashid said Iraq intended to export more than 400 million
barrels during the current six-month phase of the U.N. program. He
said Iraqi exports should average 2.5 million barrels a day. If
prices hold, Iraq should earn up to $18 billion this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-22-00 2125 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
