<HEADLINE> Fugitive Wanted Since '91 Caught  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- A man who had been a fugitive since he was charged
with killing his estranged wife in New York in 1991 was caught in
Central America and brought back to the United States on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Grullon was captured Friday evening in Panama by U.S. and
Panamanian authorities and was brought to Miami, said Deputy U.S.
Marshal John D. Amat.
</P>
<P>
   Grullon was turned over to the Miami-Dade Police Department,
which did not immediately return a phone call left Saturday.
Grullon was flown to Miami because there was not a direct flight to
New York, Amat said.
</P>
<P>
   Amat said Grullon's first court appearance would likely be in
Miami, possibly Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's here now, he's on our soil,'' said Detective Sgt. Gene
Buonanno of the Tarrytown, N.Y., Police Department. ''Now he's
mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Grullon was indicted by a grand jury in Westchester County in
December 1991 on charges he killed his estranged wife, Yolina
Camacho.
</P>
<P>
   He fled to the Dominican Republic. He was arrested and spent
several months in jail there before being released on bail and
disappearing, authorities said.
</P>
</TEXT>
