<HEADLINE> Jail's record keeper admits stealing $50,000  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GOSHEN, N.Y. (AP) - The former record-keeper at the Orange
County Jail, who disappeared the day he was indicted, has admitted
stealing more than $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   William Stenson, 57, a former lieutenant with the Orange County
Sheriff's Department, pleaded guilty Friday to second-degree grand
larceny. He faces up to 12 years in state prison when he is
sentenced Sept. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Stenson was indicted on Feb. 25, 1998 on charges that he
pocketed more than $50,000 in bail and checks from prisoners'
accounts between Jan. 1, 1996 and Feb. 25, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The day of the indictment, he took off, disappearing for nearly
two years. In February of this year, he crossed the Mexican border
and surrendered to the FBI in Laredo, Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
