<HEADLINE> Chargers' Leaf: No Shoulder Pain  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Ryan Leaf reported no discomfort in his
surgically repaired right shoulder Saturday, one day after his most
extensive workout in a year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything feels great,'' the quarterback said. ''There was no
swelling or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers hope Leaf, who missed the 1999 season, can rebound
and challenge Jim Harbaugh for the top spot. Leaf, selected second
overall in the 1998 draft, began his rookie season as the starter,
before being benched after throwing two touchdown passes and 15
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf's development wasn't the lone bright spot at the team's
second day of practices at UC San Diego. Tests showed fullback Fred
McCrary has a strained patella tendon in his left knee, and nothing
more serious, after getting hurt on the opening day.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said please Lord, don't let it be the ACL,'' said McCrary,
the team's top special teams player last year. ''It was a loud pop
and it started burning. I was worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback DeRon Jenkins, a free-agent pickup from Baltimore,
didn't work after hurting a muscle in his foot. Jenkins, like wide
receiver Curtis Conway (hamstring) could return to practice on
Monday, according to coach Mike Riley.
</P>
<P>
   Middle linebacker Eric Hill was absent after suffering a pinched
nerve on Friday. For Hill, a 12-year pro, it is a recurring injury,
and one that has Riley concerned.
</P>
</TEXT>
