<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indianapolis Off-Duty Cop Killed  </HEADLINE>
By AMY FORLITI
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- A small-town police officer, despondent over
the suicide of his girlfriend, apparently caused his own death
Saturday when police officers shot him after he aimed a pistol at
them.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Pittsboro reserve Officer Darian Gipson, 28,
may have wanted the officers to shoot him -- a situation known as
police-assisted suicide, or ''suicide by cop.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He didn't leave a note or anything like that,'' Indianapolis
police Sgt. Paul Ciesielski said. ''But all indications would lead
us to believe that yes, this was a suicide by cop.
</P>
<P>
   ''He had every opportunity to put the weapon down.''
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis police pleaded with Gipson to drop his weapon,
after he held it to his head several times and fired several shots
into the air outside a nightclub on the city's west side about
12:20 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ''He did at one point threaten the officers, saying he was going
to take them with him,'' Ciesielski said.
</P>
<P>
   Ciesielski said officers fired five shots, but it was unclear
how many had struck Gipson. Autopsy results were pending Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Gipson had been a reserve officer in Pittsboro, a small town
about 20 miles west of Indianapolis, since November 1997, said his
chief, Christi Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   He become depressed and was put on leave after he discovered his
live-in girlfriend had used his gun to kill herself in the couple's
apartment on Father's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a small town, so as a reserve officer, he didn't see
much,'' Patterson said. ''For him to walk in there and find her,
was probably the worst thing he's ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities took Gipson's gun after that incident, but it was
returned to him Thursday, said Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   She said Gipson had been counseled by clergymen and doctors and
was taking an anti-depressant, and seemed to be feeling better
until Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he told a lot of us what we wanted to hear -- that he
was fine, when in actuality he wasn't,'' Patterson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-22-00 2153 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000722.0159 </DOCNO>
