<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sea lampreys make unwelcome return to Lake Champlain  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PLATTSBURGH, N.Y. (AP) - The end of a successful program to rid
Lake Champlain of parasitic sea lampreys means anglers are once
again hauling out fish that show obvious signs of attacks.
</P>
<P>
   New York and Vermont, with funding from the federal government
and help from the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, used chemicals to
treat feeder streams in from 1989 to 1997 and recorded a high
number of lamprey deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Anglers loved it, saying they were catching stronger, larger and
healthier fish.
</P>
<P>
   But the federal government won't renew the $8 million in funding
until an environmental impact statement is completed and a future
lamprey management plan accepted, something that may take until
summer of 2001. Even then, it will take a number of years before
the treatment program becomes effective.
</P>
<P>
   New York has been funding an interim program and has treated
some of the rivers on its side of the lake but Vermont and the U.S.
Fish and Wildlife Service have not had the funding to continue
treatments in Vermont streams.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, anglers will have to risk catching fish that
show the scars of lamprey attacks. Mature sea lampreys attach
themselves to game fish, feeding on the blood of lake trout, salmon
and other species.
</P>
<P>
   ''Weve certainly received plenty of calls from some very unhappy
fishermen,'' said Lawrence Nashett, senior aquatic biologist for
the Department of Environmental Conservation at Ray Brook.
</P>
<P>
   One angler called to report that an Atlantic salmon he had
caught looked like it had ''dreadlocks'' because two or three
lampreys were still clinging to its body, Nashett said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-22-00 2250 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000722.0172 </DOCNO>
