<HEADLINE> Rockies 9, Padres 4  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Todd Helton went 3-for-5 with a three-run homer
and Larry Walker added three RBIs as the Colorado Rockies ended a
three-game losing streak Saturday night with a 9-4 victory over the
San Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Mayne and Neifi Perez had three hits each for the Rockies
who won for only the third time in 16 games. Gabe White (7-1)
worked 2 2-3 innings and struck out four to earn the win in relief.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko had two hits and drove in three runs and Phil Nevin
added two hits, including his 19th home run, for the Padres who
lost for the third time in six games. Matt Clement (9-9) lasted
four innings and allowed eight runs and 11 hits.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres took a 1-0 lead in the first inning. Eric Owens
slapped a single to right, moved to second on a groundout and
scored on Kelsko's double.
</P>
<P>
   Helton's 24th homer highlighted a four-run first. Brian Hunter
singled and Perez doubled to open the inning. Hunter came home on
Walker's groundout and after Jeff Cirillo walked, Helton hit an 0-2
fastball into the right field seats to score Perez and Cirillo.
</P>
<P>
   Walker singled off Clement's glove with two outs in the second
to score Hunter, extending the lead to 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   Nevin hit a two-out solo homer in the third.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom half, Mayne drove in a run with a single and then
scored when third baseman Nevin mishandled Hunter's grounder. An
inning later, Mayne's two-out RBI single made it 8-2.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko's two-run double in the fifth cut the lead to 8-4. The
Rockies escaped further damage when Klesko was thrown out at the
plate on a relay by second baseman Mike Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   Walker's sacrifice fly in the seventh extended the lead to 9-4.
</P>
<P>
Notes: An MRI test taken Thursday on the right shoulder of RHP
Steve Montgomery revealed a partially torn rotator cuff. ... San
Diego first-base coach Alan Trammell will miss Sunday's game to
attend the Hall of Fame induction ceremonies of Sparky Anderson,
his manager with the Detroit Tigers. ... Clement tied a club record
for 16 wild pitches in a season held by Steve Arlin (1972) and
Sterling Hitchcock (1999). ... Rockies starter Kevin Jarvis, who
has allowed 21 homers this year, lasted just 4 2-3 innings and
failed to get his third win for the eighth straight start. ... San
Diego's Dave Mauer worked two innings of relief in his major league
debut.
</P>
